INSERT INTO `lesson` VALUES ('1b6ff457-4fc6-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','2b4f1c0b-4fc4-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Lesson 2.1: CommonJS Modules','mixed',1,'Node.js uses the CommonJS module system (require / module.exports).','## Example (math.js):\n\n```const add = (a, b) => a + b;\nconst subtract = (a, b) => a - b;\n\nmodule.exports = { add, subtract };```\n\n## Usage (app.js):\n```const math = require(\'./math\');\nconsole.log(math.add(5, 3)); // 8```\n\n## Question:\ndefine greet function that take one parameter called name and add function take two parameters called a,b then use them.\n### Note: for usege use Alex name with (Hello Alex, Welcome to Node.js!) sentence for greeting , 5 for a and 3 for b.\n\n{{starter:\n// Define your functions here\n\nfunction greet(name) {\n  \n}\n\n}}\n\n\n\n{{answer:\nHello Alex, Welcome to Node.js!\n8\n}}',NULL,1,25,1,'2026-05-14 21:52:50','2026-05-14 21:57:35',NULL,'javascript'),('1bebc57c-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1beb3952-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Differentiate relational and non-relational databases','mixed',0,'Compare relational (SQL) and non-relational (NoSQL) databases: what each stores, how they model relationships, typical query patterns, and common use-cases such as transactions, analytics, or flexible schemas. Explain why choosing the right type matters for scalability, consistency, and development speed. Give concrete examples like PostgreSQL and MongoDB, and highlight normalization, indexing, and transaction guarantees as decision factors. Pitfall: assuming one fits all.','Lesson: Differentiate relational and non-relational databases\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/IndexedDB_API\n\n- https://nodejs.org/en/docs/\n\n- https://expressjs.com/en/4x/api.html\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZS_kXvOeQ5Y}}\n\nExample:\n\n```-- Relational (SQL) table example\nCREATE TABLE users (\n  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  name VARCHAR(100),\n  email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE\n);\n\n-- Non-relational (NoSQL) document example (MongoDB-style)\n{\n  \"_id\": \"u1\",\n  \"name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"emails\": [\"a@example.com\", \"alice@work.com\"]\n}\n```\n\n','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZS_kXvOeQ5Y',1,10,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:38:31',NULL,'sql'),('1bec2d8a-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1beb3952-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Install and configure PostgreSQL locally','mixed',1,'Install PostgreSQL and perform initial configuration to run a local database instance. This lesson covers server installation, initializing a database cluster, creating a superuser and test database, starting the service, and verifying connectivity. Youظـزظــظ꓂㐀Ⰶ숥ظـز╪زll learn why a local instance is important for practicing SQL and avoid common pitfalls such as service not running, version mismatches, permissions, or port/firewall issues that block psql connections.','Lesson: Install and configure PostgreSQL locally\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://nodejs.org/en/download/\n\n- https://nodejs.org/api/child_process.html\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Console/log\n\n\nExample:\n\n```sudo apt update\nsudo apt install postgresql postgresql-contrib\n\nsudo -i -u postgres\ncreateuser --interactive\ncreatedb mydb\npsql -c \"\\l\"\n\nsudo systemctl start postgresql\nsudo systemctl enable postgresql\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Simulate installation checks\n console.log(\'checking prerequisites\') \n// simulate database initialization console.log(\'initializing database cluster\')\n// simulate starting service and verifying connection console.log(\'postgresql ready\')\n}}\n\n{{answer: checking prerequisites initializing database cluster postgresql ready}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Z7U2vE7n4I',2,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:13:26',NULL,'javascript'),('1bee7cfa-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1beb3952-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Connect to PostgreSQL using psql and pgAdmin','text',1,'Learn how to connect to a PostgreSQL server using the psql command-line client and the pgAdmin graphical interface. This lesson shows the commands and GUI steps to authenticate, run queries, and inspect databases, schemas, tables, and roles. You\'ll understand connection strings and common configuration issues such as pg_hba.conf, ports, SSL settings, and user permissions. Pitfall: mismatched credentials, firewall, or wrong host/port values prevent successful connections.','Lesson: Connect to PostgreSQL using psql and pgAdmin\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/app-psql.html\n\n- https://www.pgadmin.org/docs/pgadmin4/latest/\n\n- https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/client-authentication.html\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qw--VYLpxG4}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\npsql -h localhost -p 5432 -U myuser -d mydb\n\n-- list databases\n\\l\n\n-- connect to a different database\n\\c otherdb\n\n-- list tables in current schema\n\\dt\n\n-- run a simple query\nSELECT count(*) FROM users;\n\n-- exit\n\\q\n\n-- pgAdmin: open pgAdmin, create a new server registration with host, port, maintenance DB, username; then use the object browser to expand Databases > Schemas > Tables and use the Query Tool to run SQL.\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nnums = [1, 2, 3] print(sum(nums))\n}}\n\n{{answer: 6}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qw--VYLpxG4',3,10,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:13:31',NULL,'sql'),('1beec755-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1beb3952-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Describe schemas, tables, and common SQL data types','text',1,'This lesson explains database schemas, tables, columns, and common SQL data types (numeric, character, date/time, boolean, and binary). Youظـزظــظ꓂㐀Ⰶ숥ظـز╪زll learn how each component structures data, when to choose specific types for storage and performance, and normalization implications. Practical guidance covers precision, storage size, and indexing trade offs. Watch for common pitfalls: mismatched types, implicit conversions, and future-proofing for evolving data requirements.','Lesson: Describe schemas, tables, and common SQL data types\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Data_structures\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7S_tz1z_5bA}}\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nwords = [\"API\", \"Course\"] print(\"-\".join(w.lower() for w in words))\n}}\n\n{{answer: api-course}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7S_tz1z_5bA',4,10,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:13:36',NULL,'sql'),('1beeff3d-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1beb3952-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Explore a provided sample database and run example queries','mixed',1,'Load a provided sample dataset and run basic SELECT queries to inspect rows, columns, and schema structure. You\'ll learn how to preview table contents, filter rows, and retrieve column lists so you can validate data before writing complex queries. Why: quick inspection prevents incorrect assumptions and wasted analysis time. Pitfall: forgetting to check schema changes or NULLs can make queries return unexpected results','Lesson: Explore a provided sample database and run example queries\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/\n\n- https://expressjs.com/en/starter/installing.html\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Pzj7Aj25lw}}\n\nExample:\n\n```CREATE TABLE users (\n  id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n  name TEXT,\n  age INTEGER\n);\n\nINSERT INTO users (name, age) VALUES\n  (\'Alice\', 30),\n  (\'Bob\', 22),\n  (\'Carol\', 27);\n\n-- Inspect all rows and columns\nSELECT * FROM users;\n\n-- Preview specific columns and filter\nSELECT name, age FROM users WHERE age > 25;\n\n-- Inspect schema (SQLite example)\nPRAGMA table_info(\'users\');\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// sample SQL setup represented as a string for a browser-safe starter \n// this simulates the statements you\'d run in the SQL live editor \nconst setupSql = ` \nCREATE TABLE users ( id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT, age INTEGER ); \nINSERT INTO users (name, age) \nVALUES (\'Alice\', 30), (\'Bob\', 22), (\'Carol\', 27); `; \n// In a live SQL environment you would execute setupSql and then run the example queries \n// For this lesson starter, output a quick confirmation summary to simulate the loaded dataset \nconsole.log(\'rows 3 columns id name age\');\n}}\n\n{{answer: rows 3 columns id name age}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Pzj7Aj25lw',5,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:13:42',NULL,'javascript'),('1bf01185-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1befaa6b-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Design an ER diagram for an e-commerce schema','text',1,'Design an ER diagram capturing entities, relationships, and cardinalities for an e-commerce domain. This lesson explains what to include (customers, products, orders, order_items, payments, inventory, categories), why strong normalization and clear cardinality mapping prevents anomalies, and how to represent many-to-many and optional relationships. Pitfall: avoid over-normalizing early or omitting associative entities for many-to-many relationships, which can obscure business rules and complicate queries.','Lesson: Design an ER diagram for an e-commerce schema\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/JSON\n\n- https://expressjs.com/\n\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nnums = [1, 2, 3] print(sum(nums))\n}}\n\n{{answer: 6}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4vLs1LZqOnA',1,12,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:13:46',NULL,'sql'),('1bf04d46-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1befaa6b-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Normalize tables to Third Normal Form (3NF)','mixed',1,'Apply normalization rules to decompose tables and eliminate redundancy up to Third Normal Form (3NF). This lesson shows when and how to split relations, identify functional dependencies, and remove transitive dependencies to prevent update, insert, and delete anomalies. Learn step-by-step decomposition with SQL examples and a common pitfall: over-normalizing can hurt query performance and complicate joins. Practical checklist and verification queries included.','Lesson: Normalize tables to Third Normal Form (3NF)\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UrYLYV7WSHM}}\n\nExample:\n\n```-- denormalized initial table\nCREATE TABLE orders_denorm (\n  order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n  customer_name TEXT,\n  customer_address TEXT,\n  product_id INT,\n  product_name TEXT,\n  quantity INT\n);\n\n-- decomposition into 3NF: customers, products, orders, and order_items\nCREATE TABLE customers (\n  customer_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n  name TEXT,\n  address TEXT\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE products (\n  product_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n  name TEXT\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE orders (\n  order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n  customer_id INT,\n  FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES customers(customer_id)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE order_items (\n  order_id INT,\n  product_id INT,\n  quantity INT,\n  PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id),\n  FOREIGN KEY (order_id) REFERENCES orders(order_id),\n  FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products(product_id)\n);\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// sample denormalized table description \nconst denormTable = `\norders(order_id, customer_name, customer_address, product_id, product_name, quantity)`; \n// simulate analysis of functional dependencies and decomposition \nfunction simulateNormalizationCheck(denorm) { \n// pretend we parsed dependencies and removed transitive dependencies \n// resulting status returned as a short message return \'normalized to third normal form\'; } \n// run simulation and output result console.log(simulateNormalizationCheck(denormTable));\n}}\n\n{{answer: normalized to third normal form}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UrYLYV7WSHM',2,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:13:52',NULL,'javascript'),('1bf0fc28-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1befaa6b-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Define and apply primary, foreign, and unique keys','mixed',1,'Learn to design and implement primary, foreign, and unique keys to enforce data integrity in relational schemas. Keys prevent duplicate rows, maintain referential integrity, and support reliable joins and queries. A common pitfall is mismatched data types or missing indexes on referenced columns which causes errors or slow operations. This lesson includes clear SQL DDL examples, best practices, and a small starter script that simulates applying constraints.','Lesson: Define and apply primary, foreign, and unique keys\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Database\n\n\nExample:\n\n```CREATE TABLE users (\n  id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n  email VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n  name VARCHAR(100)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE user_profiles (\n  id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n  user_id INT NOT NULL,\n  bio TEXT,\n  FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id)\n);\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Simulate applying SQL constraints for learning (no DB connection) \n\nconst steps = [ \'apply primary key to users id\', \'apply foreign key from user profiles user id to users id\', \'apply unique key to users email\' ]; \n\nsteps.forEach(step => console.log(step)); console.log(\'constraints applied successfully\');\n}}\n\n{{answer: apply primary key to users id apply foreign key from user profiles user id to users id apply unique key to users email constraints applied successfully}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PkZNo7MFNFg',3,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:13:58',NULL,'javascript'),('1bf21c2a-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1befaa6b-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Model many-to-many relationships using junction tables','mixed',1,'Show how to model many-to-many relationships using junction tables (association tables), why they preserve normalization and referential integrity, and how to enforce constraints with composite primary keys and foreign keys. Cover common pitfalls: redundant data, missing indexes, and cascade rules that can break relations. Provide SQL examples for creating junction tables and explain join queries to query related records efficiently.','Lesson: Model many-to-many relationships using junction tables\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map\n\n- https://nodejs.org/api/console.html\n\n\nExample:\n\n```CREATE TABLE students (\n  id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n  name TEXT NOT NULL\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE courses (\n  id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n  title TEXT NOT NULL\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE students_courses (\n  student_id INTEGER NOT NULL,\n  course_id INTEGER NOT NULL,\n  PRIMARY KEY (student_id, course_id),\n  FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES students(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  FOREIGN KEY (course_id) REFERENCES courses(id) ON DELETE CASCADE\n);\n\n-- Query: find courses for a student\nSELECT c.*\nFROM courses c\nJOIN students_courses sc ON c.id = sc.course_id\nWHERE sc.student_id = 1;\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// sample domain records: students and courses \nconst students = [ { id: 1, name: \'Alice\' }, { id: 2, name: \'Bob\' } ]; \n\nconst courses = [ { id: 10, title: \'SQL Basics\' }, { id: 20, title: \'JavaScript\' } ]; \n\n// junction table rows (many-to-many associations) \nconst enrollments = [ { studentId: 1, courseId: 10 }, { studentId: 2, courseId: 10 }, { studentId: 1, courseId: 20 } ]; \n// count junction rows and print summary \n\nconst junctionCount = enrollments.length; console.log(\'junction rows \' + junctionCount);\n}}\n\n{{answer: junction rows 3}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4i9qkQfH0mA',4,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:14:03',NULL,'javascript'),('1bf290d7-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1befaa6b-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Translate ER diagrams into CREATE TABLE statements','mixed',1,'Convert an ER diagram into SQL CREATE TABLE statements by selecting appropriate column types, primary keys, foreign keys, and constraints. Learn to map entities, attributes, and relationships (one-to-many, many-to-many) into normalized tables and junction tables while establishing referential integrity. Why it matters: correct mappings prevent data anomalies. Pitfall: mismatched types or missing ON DELETE/UPDATE behavior breaking foreign key relationships.','Lesson: Translate ER diagrams into CREATE TABLE statements\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nExample:\n\n```CREATE TABLE customers (\n  customer_id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n  email VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE NOT NULL\n);\nCREATE TABLE products (\n  product_id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  name VARCHAR(150) NOT NULL,\n  price DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL\n);\nCREATE TABLE orders (\n  order_id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  customer_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES customers(customer_id),\n  order_date DATE NOT NULL\n);\nCREATE TABLE order_items (\n  order_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES orders(order_id),\n  product_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES products(product_id),\n  quantity INTEGER NOT NULL, PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id)\n);\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Simulate tables derived from an ER diagram \nconst tables = [ \'customers\', \'products\', \'orders\', \'order_items\' ]; \n\n// Build a status message and print it to the console \nconst message = \'created tables \' + tables.join(\' \'); console.log(message);\n}}\n\n{{answer: created tables customers products orders order_items}}',NULL,5,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:14:07',NULL,'javascript'),('1bf32b27-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1bf2eec0-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Write SELECT queries using WHERE to filter rows','code_example',1,'Learn to use WHERE clauses to filter SELECT results by column conditions. This lesson covers equality, ranges, pattern matching, NULL checks, and combining predicates with AND/OR. You\'ll see why filtering reduces data transferred and speeds queries, and practice correct operator precedence. Pitfalls include NULL semantics, type mismatches, and filtering before aggregation ظـزظــظ꓂㐀Ⰶ숥ظ꓂㐀樆㐥 甀猀攀 䠀䄀嘀䤀一䜀 昀漀爀 最爀漀甀瀀攀搀 昀椀氀琀攀爀猀⸀ 䠀愀渀搀猀ⴀ漀渀 攀砀愀洀瀀氀攀猀 猀栀漀眀 琀礀瀀椀挀愀氀 圀䠀䔀刀䔀 氀漀最椀挀 愀渀搀 挀漀洀洀漀渀 洀椀猀琀愀欀攀猀⸀✀Ⰰ✀䰀攀猀猀漀渀㨀 圀爀椀琀攀 匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 焀甀攀爀椀攀猀 甀猀椀渀最 圀䠀䔀刀䔀 琀漀 昀椀氀琀攀爀 爀漀眀猀尀渀尀渀㸀 一漀琀攀㨀 䰀椀瘀攀 䨀愀瘀愀匀挀爀椀瀀琀 攀搀椀琀漀爀 爀甀渀猀 椀渀 琀栀攀 戀爀漀眀猀攀爀⸀ 䄀瘀漀椀搀 怀爀攀焀甀椀爀攀怀Ⰰ 怀瀀爀漀挀攀猀猀怀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 猀攀爀瘀攀爀 猀琀愀爀琀甀瀀 挀漀搀攀 栀攀爀攀⸀尀渀尀渀唀猀攀昀甀氀 刀攀猀漀甀爀挀攀猀㨀尀渀尀渀ⴀ 栀琀琀瀀猀㨀⼀⼀搀攀瘀攀氀漀瀀攀爀⸀洀漀稀椀氀氀愀⸀漀爀最⼀攀渀ⴀ唀匀⼀搀漀挀猀⼀圀攀戀⼀䨀愀瘀愀匀挀爀椀瀀琀⼀刀攀昀攀爀攀渀挀攀⼀䜀氀漀戀愀氀开伀戀樀攀挀琀猀⼀䄀爀爀愀礀⼀昀椀氀琀攀爀尀渀尀渀䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀尀渀尀渀怀怀怀挀漀搀攀尀渀ⴀⴀ 猀攀氀攀挀琀 愀挀琀椀瘀攀 甀猀攀爀猀 漀氀搀攀爀 琀栀愀渀 ㈀㔀尀渀匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 椀搀Ⰰ 渀愀洀攀Ⰰ 愀最攀尀渀䘀刀伀䴀 甀猀攀爀猀尀渀圀䠀䔀刀䔀 愀最攀 㸀 ㈀㔀 䄀一䐀 愀挀琀椀瘀攀 㴀 琀爀甀攀㬀尀渀尀渀ⴀⴀ 昀椀渀搀 渀愀洀攀猀 琀栀愀琀 猀琀愀爀琀 眀椀琀栀 愀尀渀匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 渀愀洀攀尀渀䘀刀伀䴀 甀猀攀爀猀尀渀圀䠀䔀刀䔀 渀愀洀攀 䰀䤀䬀䔀 尀✀愀─尀✀㬀尀渀尀渀ⴀⴀ 挀栀攀挀欀 昀漀爀 洀椀猀猀椀渀最 攀洀愀椀氀尀渀匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 ⨀尀渀䘀刀伀䴀 甀猀攀爀猀尀渀圀䠀䔀刀䔀 攀洀愀椀氀 䤀匀 一唀䰀䰀㬀尀渀尀渀ⴀⴀ 瀀爀攀挀攀搀攀渀挀攀 愀渀搀 最爀漀甀瀀椀渀最 攀砀愀洀瀀氀攀尀渀匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 ⨀尀渀䘀刀伀䴀 甀猀攀爀猀尀渀圀䠀䔀刀䔀 愀挀琀