(amount) OVER (ORDER BY sale_date ROWS BETWEEN 2 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) AS moving_avg_3\nFROM sales;\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nconst sales = [ { region: \'North\', date: \'2026-01-01\', amount: 100 }, { region: \'North\', date: \'2026-01-02\', amount: 200 }, { region: \'North\', date: \'2026-01-03\', amount: 420 } ]; const northSales = sales.filter(s => s.region === \'North\'); let running = 0; const runningTotals = northSales.map(s => { running += s.amount; return { date: s.date, amount: s.amount, running }; }); // final summary printed to the console console.log(\'final running total \' + runningTotals[runningTotals.length - 1].running);\n}}\n\n{{answer: final running total 720}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jt3bB9X7m7I',3,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:16:13',NULL,'javascript'),('1bf9b0f6-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1bf75341-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Use GROUPING SETS, ROLLUP, and CUBE for multi-level aggregations','mixed',1,'Learn to create multi-dimensional summaries with GROUPING SETS, ROLLUP, and CUBE to produce consolidated aggregation reports across multiple hierarchies (for example region, product, year). This lesson shows when to prefer each construct, how to interpret NULLs and GROUPING() markers, and how to avoid double-counting or missing subtotals. Common pitfall: misunderstanding how NULLs and grouping metadata map to subtotal rows, producing incorrect rollups.','Lesson: Use GROUPING SETS, ROLLUP, and CUBE for multi-level aggregations\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\n\nExample:\n\n```/* Sample table: sales(region, product, year, amount) */\n\n-- GROUPING SETS: explicit multiple groupings\nSELECT\n  region,\n  product,\n  SUM(amount) AS total_sales\nFROM sales\nGROUP BY GROUPING SETS ((region, product), (region), (product), ());\n\n-- ROLLUP: hierarchical subtotals (region -> product -> grand total)\nSELECT\n  region,\n  product,\n  SUM(amount) AS total_sales\nFROM sales\nGROUP BY ROLLUP(region, product);\n\n-- CUBE: all combinations of the given dimensions\nSELECT\n  region,\n  product,\n  SUM(amount) AS total_sales\nFROM sales\nGROUP BY CUBE(region, product);\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nconst sales = [ { region: \'north\', product: \'widget\', amount: 4000 }, { region: \'south\', product: \'gadget\', amount: 6000 } ]; const total = sales.reduce((sum, row) => sum + row.amount, 0); console.log(\'grand total \' + total);\n}}\n\n{{answer: grand total 10000}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qpk7hZp4Hb4',4,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:16:50',NULL,'javascript'),('1bfa464d-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1bfa0ae5-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Write INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, and FULL JOINs to combine tables','code_example',1,'Learn to write INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, and FULL JOINs to merge rows from related tables. This lesson explains when each join returns matching rows, retains unmatched rows, and how join direction affects results. You\'ll see SQL examples combining customers and orders, learn to choose joins for reporting or data repair, and avoid common pitfalls like unintended row multiplication from missing join conditions or confusing NULLs in outer joins.','Lesson: Write INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, and FULL JOINs to combine tables\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/queries-table-expressions.html#QUERIES-JOIN\n\n- https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/join.html\n\n- https://www.w3schools.com/sql/sql_join.asp\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9yeOJ0ZMUYw}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\n-- inner join: only rows with matching customer and order\nSELECT c.id AS customer_id, c.name, o.id AS order_id\nFROM customers c\nINNER JOIN orders o\n  ON c.id = o.customer_id;\n\n-- left join: all customers, orders when they exist\nSELECT c.id AS customer_id, c.name, o.id AS order_id\nFROM customers c\nLEFT JOIN orders o\n  ON c.id = o.customer_id;\n\n-- right join: all orders, customers when they exist\nSELECT c.id AS customer_id, c.name, o.id AS order_id\nFROM customers c\nRIGHT JOIN orders o\n  ON c.id = o.customer_id;\n\n-- full outer join: union of left and right behavior\nSELECT c.id AS customer_id, c.name, o.id AS order_id\nFROM customers c\nFULL OUTER JOIN orders o\n  ON c.id = o.customer_id;\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// sample in-memory tables: customers and orders const customers = [ { id: 1, name: \'Alice\' }, { id: 2, name: \'Bob\' }, { id: 3, name: \'Cara\' } ]; const orders = [ { id: 101, customer_id: 1 }, { id: 102, customer_id: 2 }, { id: 103, customer_id: 4 } // no matching customer ]; // inner: count of distinct customers that have at least one order const innerCount = new Set( orders.filter(o => customers.some(c => c.id === o.customer_id)) .map(o => o.customer_id) ).size; // left join rows: for each customer, count matching orders or one row with nulls if none const leftRows = customers.reduce((acc, c) => { const matches = orders.filter(o => o.customer_id === c.id).length; return acc + (matches > 0 ? matches : 1); }, 0); // right: number of orders that have a matching customer const rightCount = orders.filter(o => customers.some(c => c.id === o.customer_id)).length; // full: left rows plus orders that have no matching customer const unmatchedOrders = orders.filter(o => !customers.some(c => c.id === o.customer_id)).length; const fullRows = leftRows + unmatchedOrders; console.log(`inner ${innerCount} left ${leftRows} right ${rightCount} full ${fullRows}`);\n}}\n\n{{answer: inner 2 left 3 right 2 full 4}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9yeOJ0ZMUYw',1,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:15:37',NULL,'javascript'),('1bfad9e2-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1bfa0ae5-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Use CROSS JOIN and SELF JOIN to handle Cartesian and hierarchical queries','code_example',1,'This lesson demonstrates how to use CROSS JOIN to produce Cartesian products and SELF JOIN to traverse hierarchical relationships such as manager-subordinate links. Learn when to use each join, examine compact SQL examples, and avoid a common pitfall: unintended Cartesian explosion when you omit join conditions. Includes runnable starter code that simulates a cross join count and a concise SELF JOIN example for hierarchies.','Lesson: Use CROSS JOIN and SELF JOIN to handle Cartesian and hierarchical queries\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/flatMap\n\nExample:\n\n```code\n/* CROSS JOIN: every department paired with every employee */\nSELECT d.name AS department, e.name AS employee\nFROM departments d\nCROSS JOIN employees e;\n\n/* SELF JOIN: employees with their managers (hierarchical) */\nSELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager\nFROM employees e\nLEFT JOIN employees m ON e.manager_id = m.id\nWHERE e.manager_id IS NOT NULL;\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// small in-memory tables to simulate SQL tables const departments = [ { id: 1, name: \'Sales\' }, { id: 2, name: \'HR\' }, { id: 3, name: \'IT\' } ]; const employees = [ { id: 1, name: \'Alice\', manager_id: null }, { id: 2, name: \'Bob\', manager_id: 1 } ]; // compute cross join count (departments x employees) let count = 0; for (let d of departments) { for (let e of employees) { count++; } } // output must match expectedOutput exactly console.log(`cross join rows ${count}`);\n}}\n\n{{answer: cross join rows 6}}',NULL,2,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:16:01',NULL,'javascript'),('1bfbd5ff-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1bfa0ae5-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Construct correlated and non-correlated subqueries','code_example',1,'Learn how to write correlated and non-correlated subqueries in SELECT, FROM, and WHERE contexts to express nested logic. Why: nested queries let you compare per-row values, compute aggregations, and test existence where single-level queries fall short. Pitfall: correlated subqueries can be much slower than non-correlated ones or equivalent JOINsظـزظــظ꓂㐀Ⰶ숥ظ꓂㐀樆㐥瀆爀攀昀攀爀 搀攀爀椀瘀攀搀 琀愀戀氀攀猀 漀爀 樀漀椀渀猀 眀栀攀渀 瀀攀爀昀漀爀洀愀渀挀攀 洀愀琀琀攀爀猀⸀✀Ⰰ✀䰀攀猀猀漀渀㨀 䌀漀渀猀琀爀甀挀琀 挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 愀渀搀 渀漀渀ⴀ挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 猀甀戀焀甀攀爀椀攀猀尀渀尀渀㸀 一漀琀攀㨀 䰀椀瘀攀 䨀愀瘀愀匀挀爀椀瀀琀 攀搀椀琀漀爀 爀甀渀猀 椀渀 琀栀攀 戀爀漀眀猀攀爀⸀ 䄀瘀漀椀搀 怀爀攀焀甀椀爀攀怀Ⰰ 怀瀀爀漀挀攀猀猀怀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 猀攀爀瘀攀爀 猀琀愀爀琀甀瀀 挀漀搀攀 栀攀爀攀⸀尀渀尀渀䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀尀渀尀渀怀怀怀挀漀搀攀尀渀ⴀⴀ 一漀渀ⴀ挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 猀甀戀焀甀攀爀礀 椀渀 圀䠀䔀刀䔀㨀 挀漀洀瀀愀爀攀 搀攀瀀愀爀琀洀攀渀琀 愀瘀最 琀漀 漀瘀攀爀愀氀氀 愀瘀最尀渀匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 搀攀瀀琀开椀搀尀渀䘀刀伀䴀 搀攀瀀愀爀琀洀攀渀琀猀尀渀圀䠀䔀刀䔀 愀瘀最开猀愀氀愀爀礀 㸀 ⠀尀渀  匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 䄀嘀䜀⠀猀愀氀愀爀礀⤀尀渀  䘀刀伀䴀 攀洀瀀氀漀礀攀攀猀尀渀⤀㬀尀渀尀渀ⴀⴀ 䌀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 猀甀戀焀甀攀爀礀 椀渀 圀䠀䔀刀䔀㨀 攀洀瀀氀漀礀攀攀 愀戀漀瘀攀 琀栀攀椀爀 搀攀瀀愀爀琀洀攀渀琀 愀瘀攀爀愀最攀尀渀匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 攀⸀攀洀瀀氀漀礀攀攀开椀搀Ⰰ 攀⸀猀愀氀愀爀礀尀渀䘀刀伀䴀 攀洀瀀氀漀礀攀攀猀 攀尀渀圀䠀䔀刀䔀 攀⸀猀愀氀愀爀礀 㸀 ⠀尀渀  匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 䄀嘀䜀⠀攀㈀⸀猀愀氀愀爀礀⤀尀渀  䘀刀伀䴀 攀洀瀀氀漀礀攀攀猀 攀㈀尀渀  圀䠀䔀刀䔀 攀㈀⸀搀攀瀀琀开椀搀 㴀 攀⸀搀攀瀀琀开椀搀尀渀⤀㬀尀渀尀渀ⴀⴀ 匀甀戀焀甀攀爀礀 椀渀 䘀刀伀䴀 ⠀搀攀爀椀瘀攀搀 琀愀戀氀攀⤀ 甀猀攀搀 氀椀欀攀 愀 琀攀洀瀀漀爀愀爀礀 爀攀氀愀琀椀漀渀尀渀匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 搀⸀搀攀瀀琀开椀搀Ⰰ 搀⸀愀瘀最开猀愀氀尀渀䘀刀伀䴀 ⠀尀渀  匀䔀䰀䔀䌀吀 搀攀瀀琀开椀搀Ⰰ 䄀嘀䜀⠀猀愀氀愀爀礀⤀ 䄀匀 愀瘀最开猀愀氀尀渀  䘀刀伀䴀 攀洀瀀氀漀礀攀攀猀尀渀  䜀刀伀唀倀 䈀夀 搀攀瀀琀开椀搀尀渀⤀ 搀尀渀圀䠀䔀刀䔀 搀⸀愀瘀最开猀愀氀 㸀 㜀　　　　㬀尀渀怀怀怀尀渀尀渀䰀椀瘀攀 䌀漀搀椀渀最 吀愀猀欀㨀尀渀尀渀刀甀渀 琀栀攀 猀琀愀爀琀攀爀 挀漀搀攀Ⰰ 琀栀攀渀 挀漀洀瀀氀攀琀攀 琀栀攀 吀伀䐀伀猀⸀尀渀尀渀笀笀猀琀愀爀琀攀爀㨀尀渀⼀⼀ 匀椀洀甀氀愀琀攀 愀 渀漀渀ⴀ挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 猀甀戀焀甀攀爀礀 琀栀愀琀 爀攀琀甀爀渀猀 愀 最氀漀戀愀氀 愀最最爀攀最愀琀攀 爀攀猀甀氀琀 挀漀渀猀琀 渀漀渀䌀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀刀漀眀猀 㴀 ㈀㬀 ⼀⼀ 匀椀洀甀氀愀琀攀 愀 挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 猀甀戀焀甀攀爀礀 琀栀愀琀 爀攀琀甀爀渀猀 瀀攀爀ⴀ爀漀眀 洀愀琀挀栀攀猀 挀漀渀猀琀 挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀刀漀眀猀 㴀 ㌀㬀 ⼀⼀ 伀甀琀瀀甀琀 琀栀攀 猀椀洀甀氀愀琀攀搀 爀攀猀甀氀琀猀 愀猀 椀昀 琀栀攀礀 挀愀洀攀 昀爀漀洀 匀儀䰀 焀甀攀爀椀攀猀 挀漀渀猀漀氀攀⸀氀漀最⠀尀✀渀漀渀 挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 爀漀眀猀 ㈀尀✀⤀㬀 挀漀渀猀漀氀攀⸀氀漀最⠀尀✀挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 爀漀眀猀 ㌀尀✀⤀㬀尀渀紀紀尀渀尀渀笀笀愀渀猀眀攀爀㨀 渀漀渀 挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 爀漀眀猀 ㈀ 挀漀爀爀攀氀愀琀攀搀 爀漀眀猀 ㌀紀紀✀Ⰰ一唀䰀䰀Ⰰ㌀Ⰰ㄀㔀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ✀㈀　㈀㘀ⴀ　㔀ⴀ㄀㘀 ㄀㤀㨀㐀㠀㨀㐀㜀✀Ⰰ✀㈀　㈀㘀ⴀ　㔀ⴀ㄀㘀 ㈀　㨀㄀㜀㨀　㌀✀Ⰰ一唀䰀䰀Ⰰ✀樀愀瘀愀猀挀爀椀瀀琀✀⤀Ⰰ⠀✀㄀戀昀挀㤀　㜀愀ⴀ㔀㄀㐀㜀ⴀ㄀㄀昀㄀ⴀ㤀愀戀攀ⴀ㘀挀　㈀攀　搀㈀㘀㠀㈀㄀✀Ⰰ✀㄀戀昀愀　愀攀㔀ⴀ㔀㄀㐀㜀ⴀ㄀㄀昀㄀ⴀ㤀愀戀攀ⴀ㘀挀　㈀