渀戀尀✀ 簀簀 搀愀琀愀吀礀瀀攀 㴀㴀㴀 尀✀樀猀漀渀尀✀⤀ 笀 爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀愀琀椀漀渀 㴀 尀✀最椀渀 爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀攀搀 昀漀爀 樀猀漀渀戀尀✀㬀 紀 攀氀猀攀 椀昀 ⠀搀愀琀愀吀礀瀀攀 㴀㴀㴀 尀✀最攀漀洀攀琀爀礀尀✀ 簀簀 搀愀琀愀吀礀瀀攀 㴀㴀㴀 尀✀戀漀砀尀✀⤀ 笀 爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀愀琀椀漀渀 㴀 尀✀最椀猀琀 爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀攀搀 昀漀爀 最攀漀洀攀琀爀椀挀 搀愀琀愀尀✀㬀 紀 攀氀猀攀 笀 爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀愀琀椀漀渀 㴀 尀✀戀琀爀攀攀 爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀攀搀 昀漀爀 攀焀甀愀氀椀琀礀 愀渀搀 爀愀渀最攀尀✀㬀 紀 挀漀渀猀漀氀攀⸀氀漀最⠀爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀愀琀椀漀渀⤀㬀尀渀紀紀尀渀尀渀笀笀愀渀猀眀攀爀㨀 最椀渀 爀攀挀漀洀洀攀渀搀攀搀 昀漀爀 樀猀漀渀戀紀紀✀Ⰰ✀栀琀琀瀀猀㨀⼀⼀眀眀眀⸀礀漀甀琀甀戀攀⸀挀漀洀⼀眀愀琀挀栀㼀瘀㴀㤀漀㜀栀夀㈀洀䜀儀洀㐀✀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ㄀㔀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ✀㈀　㈀㘀ⴀ　㔀ⴀ㄀㘀 ㄀㤀㨀㐀㠀㨀㐀㜀✀Ⰰ✀㈀　㈀㘀ⴀ　㔀ⴀ㄀㘀 ㈀　㨀㄀㔀㨀㔀㠀✀Ⰰ一唀䰀䰀Ⰰ✀樀愀瘀愀猀挀爀椀瀀琀✀⤀Ⰰ⠀✀㄀挀　　㠀昀攀㤀ⴀ㔀㄀㐀㜀ⴀ㄀㄀昀㄀ⴀ㤀愀戀攀ⴀ㘀挀　㈀攀　搀㈀㘀㠀㈀㄀✀Ⰰ✀㄀戀昀昀攀㔀　愀ⴀ㔀㄀㐀㜀ⴀ㄀㄀昀㄀ⴀ㤀愀戀攀ⴀ㘀挀　㈀攀　搀㈀㘀㠀㈀㄀✀Ⰰ✀䤀渀琀攀爀瀀爀攀琀 䔀堀倀䰀䄀䤀一 愀渀搀 䔀堀倀䰀䄀䤀一 䄀一䄀䰀夀娀䔀 漀甀琀瀀甀琀 琀漀 椀搀攀渀琀椀昀礀 戀漀琀琀氀攀渀攀挀欀猀✀Ⰰ✀挀漀搀攀开攀砀愀洀瀀氀攀✀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ✀䰀攀愀爀渀 琀漀 爀攀愀搀 䔀堀倀䰀䄀䤀一 愀渀搀 䔀堀倀䰀䄀䤀一 䄀一䄀䰀夀娀䔀 漀甀琀瀀甀琀猀 琀漀 搀椀愀最渀漀猀攀 猀氀漀眀 焀甀攀爀椀攀猀Ⰰ 瀀椀渀瀀漀椀渀琀 猀挀愀渀猀Ⰰ 椀渀攀昀昀椀挀椀攀渀琀 樀漀椀渀猀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 戀漀琀琀氀攀渀攀挀欀猀⸀ 唀渀搀攀爀猀琀愀渀搀 眀栀椀挀栀 昀椀攀氀搀猀 洀愀琀琀攀爀 ⠀挀漀猀琀Ⰰ 爀漀眀猀Ⰰ 眀椀搀琀栀Ⰰ 愀挀琀甀愀氀 琀椀洀攀Ⰰ 氀漀漀瀀猀Ⰰ 戀甀昀昀攀爀猀⤀ 愀渀搀 栀漀眀 琀漀 洀愀瀀 琀栀攀洀 琀漀 椀渀搀攀砀 愀渀搀 樀漀椀渀 猀琀爀愀琀攀最椀攀猀⸀ 圀栀礀㨀 愀挀挀甀爀愀琀攀 搀椀愀最渀漀猀椀猀 氀攀愀搀猀 琀漀 琀愀爀最攀琀攀搀 漀瀀琀椀洀椀稀愀琀椀漀渀猀⸀ 倀椀琀昀愀氀氀㨀 爀攀氀礀椀渀最 漀渀 瀀氀愀渀渀攀爀 挀漀猀琀 愀氀漀渀攀㠀䀆㈆㠆䀆䀆㠆숆¤ش┬胂㠀숆¤ش╪شEXPLAIN (estimates) vs EXPLAIN ANALYZE (actuals) differ and can mislead if misread.','Lesson: Interpret EXPLAIN and EXPLAIN ANALYZE output to identify bottlenecks\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QpF8XK1wK5c}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\n-- Example: Run an analyzed plan\nEXPLAIN ANALYZE\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE email = \'alice@example.com\';\n\n-- Typical output lines to inspect:\n-- Seq Scan on users  (cost=0.00..1000.00 rows=100000 width=200) (actual time=0.010..120.340 rows=1 loops=1)\n-- Buffers: shared hit=1200 read=50\n-- Key signs: large actual time, high rows, many loops or buffer reads indicate IO or missing index\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Simulated EXPLAIN ANALYZE plan representation const plan = [ { node: \'Seq Scan\', relation: \'users\', actualTime: [0.00, 120.34], rows: 100000 } ]; // Detect a sequential scan on the users table const seq = plan.find(p => p.node.toLowerCase().includes(\'seq\') && p.relation === \'users\'); if (seq) { console.log(\'sequential scan detected on users\'); } else { console.log(\'no sequential scan detected\'); }\n}}\n\n{{answer: sequential scan detected on users}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QpF8XK1wK5c',2,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:17:47',NULL,'javascript'),('1c014681-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1bffe50a-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Rewrite queries to leverage indexes and reduce join costs','code_example',1,'Show how to restructure queries to use existing indexes and lower join cost by reordering joins, pushing selective predicates, and converting joins to EXISTS or indexed lookups. Why: greater index selectivity reduces I/O, CPU, and memory, yielding faster join performance. Pitfall: non-sargable expressions, predicates applied after joins, or joining on non-indexed columns prevents index use and causes expensive full-table scans.','Lesson: Rewrite queries to leverage indexes and reduce join costs\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Oe421EPjeBE}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\n-- Original: predicate on joined table, may force large join\nSELECT o.id, o.total\nFROM orders o\nJOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.id\nWHERE LOWER(c.email) = \'foo@example.com\';\n\n-- Rewritten: predicate pushed to an indexed lookup and using EXISTS\nSELECT o.id, o.total\nFROM orders o\nWHERE EXISTS (\n  SELECT 1 FROM customers c\n  WHERE c.id = o.customer_id\n    AND c.email = \'foo@example.com\'\n);\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Original unoptimized query example const originalQuery = \"SELECT o.* FROM orders o JOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.id WHERE c.country = \'US\'\"; // Optimized rewrite suggestion (push predicate to indexed lookup) const optimizedQuery = \"SELECT o.* FROM orders o WHERE o.customer_id IN (SELECT id FROM customers WHERE country = \'US\')\"; // Simulate before/after row counts observed in plan estimates const rowsBefore = 12000; const rowsAfter = 3; console.log(\"rows returned 3\");\n}}\n\n{{answer: rows returned 3}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Oe421EPjeBE',3,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:17:52',NULL,'javascript'),('1c01df10-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1bffe50a-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Implement table partitioning and physical clustering for large tables','code_example',1,'Learn practical strategies for partitioning large tables and using physical clustering (CLUSTER) to improve query performance and maintenance. This lesson shows when to use range, list, and hash partitioning, how to create partitions, and how to apply CLUSTER or equivalent to group rows on disk for better locality. Covers trade-offs: maintenance overhead, planning keys, increased complexity, and pitfalls like uneven partitions and write amplification.','Lesson: Implement table partitioning and physical clustering for large tables\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/ddl-partitioning.html\n\n- https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-cluster.html\n\n- https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/partitioning.html\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E5aF8ZrK3sA}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\nCREATE TABLE events (\n  id serial PRIMARY KEY,\n  user_id int NOT NULL,\n  event_date date NOT NULL,\n  payload jsonb\n) PARTITION BY RANGE (event_date);\n\nCREATE TABLE events_2024 PARTITION OF events\n  FOR VALUES FROM (\'2024-01-01\') TO (\'2025-01-01\');\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_events_user ON events (user_id);\nCLUSTER events USING idx_events_user;\nANALYZE events;\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// simulate SQL partitioning and clustering steps const statements = [ \"create table events (id serial primary key, user_id int, event_date date, payload jsonb) partition by range (event_date);\", \"create table events_2024 partition of events for values from (\'2024-01-01\') to (\'2025-01-01\');\", \"create index idx_events_user on events(user_id);\", \"cluster events using idx_events_user;\" ]; // no real DB calls in this browser-safe simulation // final user-visible output console.log(\"partitioning and clustering completed\");\n}}\n\n{{answer: partitioning and clustering completed}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E5aF8ZrK3sA',4,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:17:59',NULL,'javascript'),('1c02bf67-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1c0259a6-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Query and modify JSON/JSONB columns using operators and functions','code_example',1,'Learn to extract, update, and index JSON/JSONB in PostgreSQL using ->, ->>, jsonb_set, and GIN indexes. This lesson shows practical extraction, in-place updates, and index strategies to speed semi-structured queries. Why it matters: JSONB gives flexibility for evolving schemas while maintaining performance. Pitfall: forgetting appropriate indexing or excessive casting can cause slow sequential scans on large JSON documents.','Lesson: Query and modify JSON/JSONB columns using operators and functions\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/JSON/parse\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/JSON/stringify\n\n- https://expressjs.com/en/api.html#express.json\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H2bQe6G7q6c}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\n-- extract a scalar text value from a jsonb column\nSELECT data->>\'name\' AS name\nFROM users\nWHERE data->\'preferences\'->>\'newsletter\' = \'true\';\n\n-- update a nested jsonb field (create path if missing)\nUPDATE users\nSET data = jsonb_set(data, \'{profile,age}\', \'\"30\"\', true)\nWHERE id = 1;\n\n-- create a GIN index for fast jsonb containment queries\nCREATE INDEX idx_users_data_gin ON users USING gin (data jsonb_path_ops);\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// build a SQL extraction that reads a nested jsonb scalar const sqlExtract = \"SELECT data->\'user\'->> \'id\' AS user_id FROM users WHERE id = 1\"; // simulate database response for that SQL (as a browser-safe JS mock) const mockResult = { rows: [{ user_id: \'42\' }] }; // log a user-facing summary that mirrors a typical extraction step console.log(\'extracted user id 42\');\n}}\n\n{{answer: extracted user id 42}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H2bQe6G7q6c',1,15,1,'2026-05-16 19:48:47','2026-05-16 20:15:51',NULL,'javascript'),('1c03380e-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','1c0259a6-5147-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Define and query arrays, enums, and composite types','code_example',1,'Show how to define and query PostgreSQL arrays, enums, and composite types to model multi-valued and structured attributes. Learn creation, insertion, indexing, and querying patterns (containment, unnest, enum filtering, composite field access) to simplify schemas and improve query clarity. Pitfall: misuse of arrays/enums can complicate joins and indexing ظـزظــظ꓂㐀Ⰶ숥ظ꓂㐀樆㐥 欀渀漀眀 眀栀攀渀 琀漀 渀漀爀洀愀氀椀稀攀 瘀攀爀猀甀猀 甀猀椀渀最 琀栀攀猀攀 琀礀瀀攀猀 昀漀爀 爀攀愀搀ⴀ瀀攀爀昀漀爀洀愀渀挀攀 愀渀搀 挀漀洀瀀愀挀琀 猀琀漀爀愀最攀⸀✀Ⰰ✀䰀攀猀猀漀渀㨀 䐀攀昀椀渀攀 愀渀搀 焀甀攀爀礀 愀爀爀愀礀猀Ⰰ 攀渀甀洀猀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 挀漀洀瀀漀猀椀琀攀 琀礀瀀攀猀尀渀尀渀㸀 一漀琀攀㨀 䰀椀瘀攀 䨀愀瘀愀匀挀爀椀瀀琀 攀搀椀琀漀爀 爀甀渀猀 椀渀 琀栀攀 戀爀漀眀猀攀爀⸀ 䄀瘀漀椀搀 怀爀攀焀甀椀爀攀怀Ⰰ 怀瀀爀漀挀攀猀猀怀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 猀攀爀瘀攀爀 猀琀愀爀琀甀瀀 挀漀搀攀 栀攀爀攀⸀尀渀尀渀笀笀瘀椀搀攀漀㨀 栀琀琀瀀猀㨀⼀⼀眀眀眀⸀礀漀甀琀甀戀攀⸀挀漀洀⼀眀愀琀挀栀㼀瘀㴀䔀焀开渀眀䜀㐀䨀欀　儀紀紀尀渀尀渀䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀尀渀尀渀怀怀怀挀漀搀攀尀渀ⴀⴀ 挀爀攀愀琀攀 愀渀 攀渀甀洀 愀渀搀 愀 挀漀洀瀀漀猀椀琀攀 琀礀瀀攀尀渀䌀刀䔀䄀吀䔀 吀夀倀䔀 洀漀漀搀 䄀匀 䔀一唀䴀 ⠀尀✀猀愀搀尀✀Ⰰ 尀✀漀欀尀✀Ⰰ 尀✀栀愀瀀瀀礀尀✀⤀㬀尀渀䌀刀䔀䄀吀䔀 吀夀倀䔀 愀搀搀爀攀猀猀 䄀匀 ⠀猀琀爀攀攀琀 琀攀砀琀Ⰰ 挀椀琀礀 琀攀砀琀⤀㬀尀渀尀渀ⴀⴀ 琀愀戀氀攀 眀椀琀栀 愀渀 愀爀爀愀礀Ⰰ 攀渀甀洀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 挀漀洀瀀漀猀椀琀攀 挀漀氀甀洀渀尀渀