猀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 甀渀甀猀攀搀 瘀愀爀椀愀戀氀攀猀⸀ 吀栀椀猀 氀攀猀猀漀渀 琀攀愀挀栀攀猀 栀漀眀 琀漀 椀渀琀攀爀瀀爀攀琀 挀漀洀瀀椀氀攀爀 漀甀琀瀀甀琀Ⰰ 瀀爀椀漀爀椀琀椀稀攀 昀椀砀攀猀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 瘀攀爀椀昀礀 挀漀爀爀攀挀琀椀漀渀猀 眀椀琀栀 愀 猀洀愀氀氀 䌀 攀砀愀洀瀀氀攀⸀ 倀椀琀昀愀氀氀㨀 昀椀砀椀渀最 漀渀攀 攀爀爀漀爀 挀愀渀 爀攀瘀攀愀氀 漀琀栀攀爀猀樀唥Ⱕ숥┬جcompile often and address diagnostics in order.','## What is a compiler error or warning \nA **compiler error** is a diagnostic the compiler emits when it finds code it cannot translate to machine instructions (syntax problems, type mismatches). A **warning** is a lower-severity diagnostic that indicates suspicious code which still compiles but may behave incorrectly or port poorly. Both include a file name, line number, and a message that points to the problem.\n ## Why it matters Understanding diagnostics speeds development: \ninstead of guessing, you read the compiler\'s message, change the smallest broken piece, and recompile. That iterative cycle reduces time spent on obscure runtime bugs. Warnings often point to undefined behavior or portability issues that become bugs later. \n## How it works\n ### 1. Compile with a modern compiler and common flags (e.g., `gcc -Wall -Wextra`). \n### 2. Read the first diagnostic: the compiler typically reports the earliest error; later messages may depend on the first\n### 3. Fix the single issue, then recompile. Many fixes remove cascading errors. \n### 4. Treat warnings as actionable: fix obvious ones or temporarily silence a known safe case with minimal scope. \n\nExample edit-compile-debug cycle: \n- Compile: read file:line and message. \n- Edit that line to correct syntax or format specifier. \n- Recompile until no errors; then resolve warnings. \n## Common mistakes \n- Missing semicolon: compiler shows a syntax error near the previous or next token; fix by adding the semicolon on the indicated line. \n- Wrong `printf` specifier: using `%f` for an `int` may compile with a warning or undefined output; use a matching specifier like `%d`. \n- Unused variables: compiler warns about unused locals; remove the variable or use it meaningfully to silence the warning. Fix tip: compile after each change; one fix often clears several messages. \n## Summary \n- Read the compiler message first; it gives file, line, and a short description. \n- Fix the earliest error, then recompile; repeat until clean. \n- Treat warnings as important signals; correct format mismatches and unused code. \n- Use `-Wall -Wextra` during development to catch issues early.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Diagnostic-Messages.html\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/diagnostics\n\nExample:\n\n```#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main(void) {\n    int x = 10\n    printf(\"Value: %d\\n\", x); // missing semicolon above\n\nint unused; // compiler will warn about unused variable\n\nprintf(\"Percent: %f\\n\", 50); // wrong format: %f expects double, not int\n\nreturn 0;\n}\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n#include <stdio.h> \nint main(void) {\n\nint total = 2 + 4 + 6;\n\nprintf(\"%d\\n\", total);\n\nreturn 0;\n\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer: 12}}',NULL,4,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-20 23:23:52',NULL,'c'),('3c1fab94-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c1f5e4a-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Explain C Data Types and Variables','mixed',1,'Learn C built-in types, literals, declarations, initializations, and basic scope and storage duration rules. This lesson explains why choosing the right type matters for correctness and memory use, shows common literal forms and initialization patterns, and highlights the common pitfall of using uninitialized or incorrectly scoped variables that cause undefined behavior or surprising results.','## What is C data types and variables \nC **data types** define the kind of values a variable can hold (for example `int`, `double`, `char`, `size_t`), while a **variable** is a named storage location with a type. A **literal** is a fixed value written in source code (e.g., `42`, `3.14`, `\'A\'`). Declarations introduce a name and type; initialization gives it an initial value. \n## Why it matters Choosing the right type prevents incorrect calculations, excessive memory use, and platform-dependent bugs. \nCorrect initialization and understanding of **scope** (where a variable is visible) and **storage duration** (how long it exists: automatic, static, or static-duration global) avoid undefined behavior and make program flow predictable. \n## How it works \n1. Declaration and initialization: `int x = 5;` declares `x` as an `int` and initializes it to `5`. \n2. Literals: integers are written like `10`, floats like `3.14`, chars like `\'A\'`. \n3. Scope: variables declared inside a function are local (block scope); globals declared outside any function are visible across functions. \n4. Storage duration: - Automatic (local) variables are created on function entry and destroyed on return. - `static` local variables persist between calls and keep their value. - Global variables have static storage duration and persist for the program\'s life. \n\nExample behavior: a local automatic counter resets each call, a `static` local counter increments across calls, and a global counter also accumulates across calls. \n## Common mistakes \n- Using uninitialized variables: reading them causes undefined behavior; always initialize variables before use. \n- Confusing scope: declaring a variable inside a block hides a global of the same name; avoid shadowing. \n- Expecting `static` locals to be thread-safe or temporary: `static` persists for program life and must be used deliberately. \n## Summary \n- **Types** constrain values and operations (`int`, `double`, `char`, `size_t`). \n- **Initialization** prevents undefined behavior╪╕┬胂ⰀⰥ愆氀眀愀礀猀 椀渀椀琀椀愀氀椀稀攀 戀攀昀漀爀攀 甀猀攀⸀ 尀渀ⴀ ⨀⨀匀挀漀瀀攀⨀⨀ 挀漀渀琀爀漀氀猀 瘀椀猀椀戀椀氀椀琀礀㬀 ⨀⨀猀琀漀爀愀最攀 搀甀爀愀琀椀漀渀⨀⨀ 挀漀渀琀爀漀氀猀 氀椀昀攀琀椀洀攀⸀ 尀渀ⴀ 唀猀攀 怀猀琀愀琀椀挀怀 愀渀搀 怀最氀漀戀愀氀怀 眀栀攀渀 瀀攀爀猀椀猀琀攀渀挀攀 愀挀爀漀猀猀 挀愀氀氀猀 椀猀 爀攀焀甀椀爀攀搀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 瀀爀攀昀攀爀 氀漀挀愀氀 瘀愀爀椀愀戀氀攀猀 眀栀攀渀 瀀漀猀猀椀戀氀攀⸀ 尀渀怀怀怀挀 ⼀⨀ 匀栀漀爀琀 攀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀 搀攀挀氀愀爀愀琀椀漀渀猀 愀渀搀 椀渀椀琀椀愀氀椀稀愀琀椀漀渀 ⨀⼀ 尀渀椀渀琀 砀 㴀 　㬀 尀渀搀漀甀戀氀攀 礀 㴀 ㈀⸀㔀　㬀 尀渀挀栀愀爀 挀 㴀 尀✀娀尀✀㬀 尀渀挀漀渀猀琀 椀渀琀 洀愀砀 㴀 ㄀　　㬀 尀渀⼀⨀ 倀爀椀渀琀 瘀愀氀甀攀猀 ⠀椀渀琀爀漀搀甀挀攀搀 攀愀爀氀椀攀爀㨀 瀀爀椀渀琀昀⤀ ⨀⼀ 尀渀瀀爀椀渀琀昀⠀尀∀砀㴀─搀 礀㴀─⸀㈀昀 挀㴀─挀 洀愀砀㴀─搀尀尀渀尀∀Ⰰ 砀Ⰰ 礀Ⰰ 挀Ⰰ 洀愀砀⤀㬀 怀怀怀尀渀尀渀唀猀攀昀甀氀 刀攀猀漀甀爀挀攀猀㨀尀渀尀渀ⴀ 栀琀琀瀀猀㨀⼀⼀攀渀⸀挀瀀瀀爀攀昀攀爀攀渀挀攀⸀挀漀洀⼀眀⼀挀⼀氀愀渀最甀愀最攀⼀琀礀瀀攀猀尀渀尀渀䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀尀渀尀渀怀怀怀椀渀琀 愀 㴀 㔀㬀尀渀搀漀甀戀氀攀 瀀椀 㴀 ㌀⸀㄀㐀㬀尀渀挀栀愀爀 氀攀琀琀攀爀 㴀 尀✀䄀尀✀㬀尀渀挀漀渀猀琀 椀渀琀 䴀䄀堀 㴀 ㄀　㬀尀渀尀渀瀀爀椀渀琀昀⠀尀∀愀㴀─搀 瀀椀㴀─⸀㈀昀 氀攀琀琀攀爀㴀─挀 䴀䄀堀㴀─搀尀尀渀尀∀Ⰰ 愀Ⰰ 瀀椀Ⰰ 氀攀琀琀攀爀Ⰰ 䴀䄀堀⤀㬀尀渀怀怀怀尀渀尀渀䰀椀瘀攀 䌀漀搀椀渀最 吀愀猀欀㨀尀渀尀渀刀甀渀 琀栀攀 猀琀愀爀琀攀爀 挀漀搀攀Ⰰ 琀栀攀渀 挀漀洀瀀氀攀琀攀 琀栀攀 吀伀䐀伀猀⸀尀渀尀渀笀笀猀琀愀爀琀攀爀㨀尀渀⌀椀渀挀氀甀搀攀 㰀猀琀搀椀漀⸀栀㸀 尀渀椀渀琀 洀愀椀渀⠀瘀漀椀搀⤀ 笀尀渀尀渀椀渀琀 猀甀洀 㴀 　㬀尀渀尀渀昀漀爀 ⠀椀渀琀 椀 㴀 ㄀㬀尀渀尀渀椀 㰀㴀 ㌀㬀尀渀尀渀椀⬀⬀⤀ 笀尀渀尀渀猀甀洀 ⬀㴀 椀㬀尀渀尀渀紀尀渀尀渀瀀爀椀渀琀昀⠀尀∀─搀尀尀渀尀∀Ⰰ 猀甀洀⤀㬀尀渀尀渀爀攀琀甀爀渀 　㬀尀渀尀渀紀尀渀紀紀尀渀尀渀笀笀愀渀猀眀攀爀㨀 㘀紀紀✀Ⰰ一唀䰀䰀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ㄀㈀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ✀㈀　㈀㘀ⴀ　㔀ⴀ㈀　 ㈀㄀㨀㄀㠀㨀　　✀Ⰰ✀㈀　㈀㘀ⴀ　㔀ⴀ㈀　 ㈀㌀㨀㈀㜀㨀㔀㤀✀Ⰰ一唀䰀䰀Ⰰ✀挀✀⤀Ⰰ⠀✀㌀挀㈀㄀㔀㈀挀㘀ⴀ㔀㐀㜀㠀ⴀ㄀㄀昀㄀ⴀ㤀愀戀攀ⴀ㘀挀　㈀攀　搀㈀㘀㠀㈀㄀✀Ⰰ✀㌀挀㄀昀㔀攀㐀愀ⴀ㔀㐀㜀㠀ⴀ㄀㄀昀㄀ⴀ㤀愀戀攀ⴀ㘀挀　㈀攀　搀㈀㘀㠀㈀㄀✀Ⰰ✀唀猀攀 伀瀀攀爀愀琀漀爀猀 愀渀搀 䔀砀瀀爀攀猀猀椀漀渀猀 椀渀 䌀✀Ⰰ✀洀椀砀攀搀✀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ✀䰀攀愀爀渀 栀漀眀 琀漀 愀瀀瀀氀礀 䌀樀唥Ⱕ숥╪تs arithmetic, relational, logical, and bitwise operators to compute and update values; understand operator precedence and common pitfalls like integer division and unintended type promotion. This lesson shows practical examples, explains evaluation order, and highlights mistakes that cause wrong results or warnings, so you can write correct expressions and avoid surprising behaviors in real programs.','## What is operators and expressions \nOperators are the symbols that perform actions on values (operands). An **expression** combines variables, literals, and operators to produce a value. \nIn C, operators include **arithmetic** (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`), **relational** (`==`, `!=`, `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=`), **logical** (`&&`, `||`, `!`), and **bitwise** (`&`, `|`, `^`, `<<`, `>>`). Expressions evaluate according to **operator precedence** and associativity. \n\n## Why it matters Operators \nlet you compute results, test conditions, and manipulate bits╪╕┬胂ⰀⰥ昆甀渀搀愀洀攀渀琀愀氀 琀愀猀欀猀 椀渀 攀瘀攀爀礀 䌀 瀀爀漀最爀愀洀⸀ 䴀椀猀琀愀欀攀猀 猀甀挀栀 愀猀 愀猀猀甀洀椀渀最 昀氀漀愀琀椀渀最ⴀ瀀漀椀渀琀 搀椀瘀椀猀椀漀渀 昀漀爀 椀渀琀攀最攀爀猀 漀爀 洀椀砀椀渀最 猀椀最渀攀搀 愀渀搀 甀渀猀椀最渀攀搀 琀礀