 + b);\n\nreturn 0;\n\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer: 7}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l8WPWK9mS5M',2,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-20 23:47:18',NULL,'c'),('3c2289ef-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c1f5e4a-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Implement Control Flow with if, switch, and Loops','text',1,'Learn how to write conditional and iterative C code using `if/else`, `switch`, `for`, `while`, and `do/while` to control program flow. This lesson shows practical examples, explains why each construct matters, and highlights common pitfalls like off-by-one errors and incorrect fall-through in `switch` statements. By the end you\'ll write clear, predictable control flow and avoid typical beginner mistakes.','## What is control flow in C \nControl flow determines which statements execute and how often in a C program. The main constructs are **conditional statements** (`if`, `else`, `switch`) that choose a path, and **loops** (`for`, `while`, `do/while`) that repeat actions. Together they let your program make decisions and process data repeatedly. \n## Why it matters \nControl flow is essential for real-world programs: it handles input validation, branches logic based on conditions, iterates over arrays or ranges, and implements state machines. Correct use of these constructs leads to readable, maintainable, and bug-resistant code. \n## How it works \n- `if/else`: Evaluate a boolean expression; run the `if` block when true, otherwise run `else` (optional). Use `else if` for multiple disjoint branches. \n- `switch`: Compare an integral value against `case` labels; `break` prevents fall-through. Use `default` as a fallback. \n- `for`: Best for counted loops with initialization, condition, and increment in one line. \n- `while`: Repeat while a condition remains true; test before each iteration. \n- `do/while`: Execute the body at least once and test afterward. Step-by-step: write a clear condition, ensure loop termination, and prefer explicit `break`/`continue` only when they make the logic simpler. \n## Common mistakes \n- Off-by-one errors: loops that iterate one time too many or too few; fix by checking loop bounds and using `<=` vs `<` intentionally. \n- Missing `break` in `switch`: leads to unintended fall-through; add `break` after each `case` unless fall-through is desired.\n - Infinite loops: ensure loop variables change toward the terminating condition; test with small ranges. \n## Summary \n- Use `if/else` for conditional branching and `switch` for multi-way selection. \n- Use `for` for counted loops, `while` for condition-driven loops, and `do/while` when the body must run once. \n- Always verify loop bounds and add `break` in `switch` cases to avoid fall-through. \n- Test small cases to catch off-by-one and infinite loop mistakes early. \n\nExample code and the live editor exercise illustrate these constructs together so you can trace program output step by step.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/if\n\n\n\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n#include <stdio.h> \nint main(void) {\n\nint x = 2;\nif (x % 2 == 0)\n{\n    printf(\"%d is even\\n\", x);\n}\nelse\n{\n    printf(\"%d is odd\\n\", x);\n}\n\nfor (int i = 0; i < 2; i++)\n{\n    printf(\"loop %d\\n\", i);\n}\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer: 2 is even\nloop 0\nloop 1}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z6HIOj2xg9E',3,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-20 23:51:20',NULL,'c'),('3c245e0a-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c1f5e4a-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Detect and Fix Common Runtime Logic Errors','text',1,'Learn to identify and fix common runtime logic errors such as off-by-one loops and incorrect condition evaluations in C. This lesson explains why these mistakes cause wrong outputs or missed iterations, demonstrates a corrected example, and highlights debugging checks to find and prevent such issues. Watch for boundary conditions, comparison operators, and loop index types to avoid subtle, runtime-only bugs.','## What is runtime logic errors \nA **runtime logic error** occurs when a program compiles but its behavior is incorrect due to wrong use of operators, loop boundaries, or conditions. These errors do not stop compilation but lead to incorrect outputs, infinite loops, or skipped processing at run time. \n## Why it matters \nIn real programs, a single misplaced comparison or off-by-one in a loop can silently corrupt results, skip data, or cause security issues. Catching these early prevents incorrect calculations and preserves user trust and program correctness. \n## How it works \n1. Identify the symptom: wrong totals, missing items, or unexpected counts. \n2. Inspect loop boundaries and comparisons: loops that iterate over arrays should normally use `i < len`, not `i <= len`. \n3. Check operator precedence and boolean expressions: ensure `&&` and `||` combine conditions as intended and parentheses clarify intent. \n4. Verify variable types: use `size_t` for sizes and indexes to avoid signed/unsigned surprises. \n\nExample flow: determine the expected iterations, compute `len` with `sizeof`, confirm the loop uses `< len`, and only increment counters inside the intended conditional branch. \n## Common mistakes \n- Off-by-one in loops: using `<=` instead of `<` will read past the last element and can produce wrong results; fix by using `i < len` and computing `len` correctly. \n- Wrong conditional order or forgetting parentheses: combined conditions like `a > 0 && b < 5` might need parentheses when mixed with other operators; rewrite or add parentheses to be explicit. \n- Using signed index with unsigned length: comparing signed `int` index to `size_t` length can cause unexpected behavior; use `size_t` for indexes.\n\n ## Summary \n- Always compute array length with `sizeof(array) / sizeof(array[0])`. \n- Use `i < len` for iteration to avoid off-by-one errors. \n- Prefer `size_t` for sizes and indexes and print it with `%zu`. \n- Inspect conditional expressions and add parentheses for clarity. \n\nExample of a corrected loop is provided in the lesson code to demonstrate these fixes.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/for\n\n- https://www.gnu.org/software/gdb/\n\n\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stddef.h>\n\n/* Corrected off-by-one example */\nint main(void) {\n    int a[] = {10, 20, 30};\n    size_t n = sizeof(a) / sizeof(a[0]);\n    size_t i = 0;\n\nfor (i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n        printf(\"%d\\n\", a[i]);\n    }\n\nreturn 0;\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer: 10\n20\n30}}',NULL,4,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-20 23:56:38',NULL,'c'),('3c292913-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c28c53d-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Define and Use Functions and Header Files','mixed',1,'Learn how to write reusable C functions, declare prototypes, and organize code into header and source files to build modular programs. This lesson covers why prototypes and header guards matter and shows a simple, compilable example. Common pitfalls include missing prototypes (compiler warnings) and duplicate definitions when headers lack include guards.','## What is a function and header file \nA **function** is a named block of code that performs a specific task and can be called from other parts of a program. A **header file** (a file with `.h` extension) contains function prototypes, type definitions, and macro guards so multiple source files can share declarations without duplicating implementations. \n## Why it matters \nModular code improves readability and reuse: you can test functions independently, reuse utilities across programs, and keep `main.c` focused on program flow. Using headers prevents repeating prototypes and helps the compiler check calls for correct argument types. \n## How it works \n1. Create a header file (`math_utils.h`) that contains function prototypes and include guards. \n2. Implement functions in a source file (`math_utils.c`). \n3. In `main.c`, `#include \"math_utils.h\"` so the compiler knows the prototypes before use. \n4. During compilation, compile each `.c` file separately and link them together to form the final executable. Example prototype syntax: \n```int add(int a, int b); \nint multiply(int a, int b); ``` \nThe compiler needs the prototypes before calls in `main` so it can check types; linking needs exactly one implementation of each function. \n## Common mistakes \n- Missing prototypes: placing function definitions after `main` without prototypes can still work if the compiler sees the definition before use, but many compilers warn or error; fix by putting prototypes in a header and including it. \n- No include guards in headers: including the same header multiple times across files can cause duplicate-declaration or multiple-definition errors; fix by adding `#ifndef/#define/#endif` guards. \n- Implementing functions in headers: putting full function definitions in headers can cause linker errors (multiple definitions) when headers are included by more than one `.c` file; instead put definitions in `.c` files and prototypes in `.h` files. \n\n## Summary \n- **Declare prototypes** in headers and include them where needed. \n- **Implement functions** in `.c` files, keeping one definition per function. \n- **Use include guards** to prevent duplicate declarations. \n- Modular design improves reuse, testing, and compilation clarity.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/functions\n\n\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n#include <stdio.h>\n\nint add(int a, int b) {\n    return a + b;\n}\n\nint multiply(int a, int b) {\n    return a * b;\n}\n\nint main(void) {\n    printf(\"Sum: %d\\n\", add(3, 4));\n    return 0;\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer: Sum: 7}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zuegQmMdy8M',1,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-21 12:54:17',NULL,'c'),('3c2b75d6-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c28c53d-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Use Pointers to Access and Modify Memory','mixed',1,'Learn how to declare pointers, use the address-of and indirection operators to read and write memory, and modify variables through pointer references. This lesson shows why pointers let functions and code share and change data efficiently, and warns about common pitfalls like dereferencing uninitialized pointers and confusing pointer vs value operations.','## What is a pointer \nA **pointer** is a variable that stores the *memory address* of another variable. In C, you declare a pointer with a `*` (for example `int *p`) and obtain an address with the address-of operator `&` (for example `&x`). Dereferencing the pointer with `*p` accesses or modifies the value stored at that address. \n## Why it matters \nPointers let you write efficient code that modifies variables from other functions, work with arrays and buffers, and manage dynamic memory. They are fundamental to systems programming in C and are required for real-world tasks like writing data structures, I/O routines, and interfacing with hardware. \n## How it works \n1. Declare a variable (for example `int a = 10;`). \n2. Declare a pointer matching the variable type: `int *p;`. \n3. Store the variable\'s address in the pointer: `p = &a;`. \n4. Read the value through the pointer using `*p`. \n5. Modify the value through the pointer by assigning to `*p`. This changes the original variable because the pointer refers to the same memory location. \n\n## Common mistakes \n- Using an uninitialized pointer: if a pointer does not hold a valid address, dereferencing it causes undefined behavior; always initialize a pointer before dereferencing it (for example, assign an address or set it to `NULL`). \n- Confusing pointer vs value: assigning `p = a;` (value) instead of `p = &a;` (address) is a type error and indicates misunderstanding; check types and use `&` for addresses. \n- Forgetting that pointers must match types: `int *` should point to `int` storage to avoid incorrect interpretation of memory. \n\n## Summary \n- Pointers store **addresses**, not values. \n- Use `&` to get an address and `*` to access the value at that address. \n- Modifying `*p` changes the original variable that `p` points to. \n- Always initialize pointers and ensure types match to avoid undefined behavior.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/pointer\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DTxHyVn0ODg}}\n\nExample:\n\n```#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main(void)\n{\n    int x = 5;\n\nint *ptr = &x;\n\n*ptr = *ptr + 3; // modify x through the pointer\n\nprintf(\"x = %d\\n\", x);\n\nreturn 0;\n}\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n#include <stdio.h> \nint main(void) {\n\nint a = 10;\n\nint *p = &a;\n\nprintf(\"Before: a = %d\\n\", a);\n\nprintf(\"Value via pointer: %d\\n\", *p);\n\n*p = 20;\n\nprintf(\"After: a = %d\\n\", a);\n\nreturn 0;\n\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer: Before: a = 10 Value via pointer: 10 After: a = 20}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DTxHyVn0ODg',2,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-21 12:56:53',NULL,'c'),('3c2e77f0-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c28c53d-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Manipulate Arrays and C Strings with Pointers','mixed',1,'Use indexing and pointer arithmetic to traverse, read, and modify arrays and null-terminated C strings. Learn simple pointer-based routines to compute length and copy strings, print characters, and modify characters safely. This lesson highlights when to use indexing vs pointer traversal and warns about common pitfalls such as buffer overflows and forgetting the terminating \'\\0\'.','## What is pointer-based array and string traversal \nPointer-based array and string traversal means using **pointer variables** and **pointer arithmetic** (incrementing or decrementing pointers) to step through arrays and null-terminated strings (`char` arrays) instead of using only numeric indexing. In C, strings are sequences of characters ending with a `\\0` sentinel; pointers let you move through them efficiently and expressively. \n## Why it matters \nWorking directly with pointers is idiomatic C: many standard routines (like `strlen`, `strcpy`) are implemented with pointer loops. Using pointers correctly yields concise code and can be slightly faster. More importantly, understanding pointer traversal helps you avoid memory bugs such as reading past the terminating `\\0` or writing beyond an array boundary. \n## How it works \n1. Use a pointer of type `char *` to reference the current character in a string. \n2. Test `*p != \'\\0\'` to determine if you reached the end. \n3. Advance the pointer with `p++` (pointer arithmetic) to move to the next character. \n4. To modify a string in-place, ensure the array is writable (not a string literal) and then assign via `arr[i] = c` or `*(p + offset) = c`. \nExample pattern (pointer length): \n\n\n## Common mistakes \n- Forgetting the terminating `\\0`: writing a copied string without appending `\\0` produces undefined behavior; always set the final byte to `\\0` after copy. \n- Copying into an undersized buffer: ensure destination has enough space before calling pointer-copy routines. \n- Modifying string literals: string literals may be in read-only memory; only modify arrays declared as writable (e.g., `char s[] = \"hi\";`). \n\n## Summary \n- Use **pointer arithmetic** (`p++`, `p - start`) to traverse arrays and strings. \n- Check `*p != \'\\0\'` to avoid overrunning strings. \n- Always ensure destination buffers are large enough and append the `\\0` terminator when copying. \n- Prefer clear, simple pointer loops for common string routines like `strlen` and `strcpy`.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/string/byte\n\nExample:\n\n```size_t my_strlen(const char *s)\n{\n    const char *p = s;\n\nwhile (*p != \'\\0\')\n    {\n        p++;\n    }\n\nreturn (size_t)(p - s);\n}\n```\n\n\n\n{{starter:\n#include <stdio.h>\n\nsize_t string_length(const char *str)\n{\n    const char *ptr = str;\n\n    while (*ptr)\n    {\n        ptr++;\n    }\n\n    return (size_t)(ptr - str);\n}\n\nint main()\n{\n    char text[] = \"Hello World\";\n\n    printf(\"Length = %zu\\n\", string_length(text));\n\n    return 0;\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer:\nLength = 11\n}}',NULL,3,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-21 13:02:52',NULL,'c'),('3c2f13f7-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c28c53d-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Manage Dynamic Memory and Handle Memory Errors','mixed',1,'Learn to allocate, resize, and free heap memory in C using `malloc`, `realloc`, and `free`. This lesson shows why correct checks and pointer handling matter to avoid leaks, double-free, and dangling pointers, and demonstrates safe resize patterns. Common pitfalls such as ignoring NULL from allocation and failing to nullify freed pointers are highlighted with fixes and a runnable example.','## What is dynamic memory management \nDynamic memory management in C means requesting and releasing memory at runtime using the heap with functions like `malloc`, `realloc`, and `free`. Unlike automatic (stack) storage, dynamically allocated memory persists until you explicitly free it, and is accessed via **pointers**. \n## Why it matters \nPrograms that grow or shrink data structures at runtime rely on dynamic memory. Proper management prevents **memory leaks** (lost allocated blocks), **double-free** (freeing the same block twice), and **dangling pointers** (pointers to freed memory), all of which can cause crashes or security issues. \n## How it works \n1. Request memory with `malloc(size_t)` or `calloc(size_t, size_t)` and always check the returned pointer against `NULL` before use. \n2. Use the memory via pointers and array indexing (`ptr[i]`). \n3. To change size, use `realloc` carefully: assign the result to a temporary pointer and check `NULL` before overwriting the original pointer to avoid losing the original block on failure. \n4. When finished, release with `free(ptr)` and set `ptr = NULL` to avoid dangling pointers. Example safe `realloc` pattern: allocate, attempt to resize into a `tmp` pointer, check `tmp != NULL`, then assign back to the original pointer. \n## Common mistakes \n- Not checking `malloc`/`realloc` return values: on failure you may dereference `NULL` causing a crash; fix by testing for `NULL` and handling the error. \n- Overwriting the original pointer with `realloc` directly: if `realloc` returns `NULL` you lose the original pointer and leak memory; fix by using a temporary pointer. \n- Forgetting to `free` allocated memory or freeing twice: always `free` exactly once and set pointer to `NULL` after freeing to detect accidental reuse. \n## Summary \n- Use `malloc`/`calloc` to allocate and `free` to release memory. \n- Always check allocation results for `NULL`.\n- Use a temporary pointer with `realloc` to avoid leaks on failure. \n- After `free`, set pointers to `NULL` to avoid dangling pointers and double-free errors.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/memory\n\n- https://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Allocation-Functions.html\n\nExample:\n\n```#include <stdlib.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n\nint *safe_resize(int *p, size_t new_count)\n{\n    int *tmp = realloc(p, new_count * sizeof *p);\n    if (tmp == NULL)\n    {\n        return NULL;\n    }\n\nreturn tmp;\n}\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n\nint *resize_array(int *arr, size_t size)\n{\n    int *new_arr = realloc(arr, size * sizeof *arr);\n\n    if (new_arr == NULL)\n    {\n        return NULL;\n    }\n\n    return new_arr;\n}\n\nint main()\n{\n    int *numbers = malloc(3 * sizeof *numbers);\n\n    if (numbers == NULL)\n    {\n        return 1;\n    }\n\n    numbers[0] = 10;\n    numbers[1] = 20;\n    numbers[2] = 30;\n\n    numbers = resize_array(numbers, 5);\n\n    if (numbers == NULL)\n    {\n        return 1;\n    }\n\n    numbers[3] = 40;\n    numbers[4] = 50;\n\n    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++)\n    {\n        printf(\"%d \", numbers[i]);\n    }\n\n    free(numbers);\n\n    return 0;\n}\n}}\n\n{{answer: 10 20 30 40 50 }}',NULL,4,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-21 13:06:34',NULL,'c'),('3c346353-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c317fc8-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Perform File Input and Output in C','mixed',1,'Learn to open, read, write, and close files in C using the standard FILE* API (fopen, fclose, fwrite, fgets). This lesson demonstrates writing text to a file, reading it back, and checking return values to detect errors. Why it matters: file I/O provides persistent storage for programs. Pitfall: forgetting to check return values or to close files can cause data loss or resource leaks.','## What is file input/output in C \nFile input/output in C uses the standard library FILE* stream API to work with files on disk. Common functions include `fopen` (open a stream), `fclose` (close a stream), `fwrite`/`fread` (binary blocks), and `fgets`/`fprintf` (text). Files are addressed by `FILE*` pointers; operations return values that must be checked for errors. \n## Why it matters \nFiles let programs persist data beyond a run: configuration, logs, saved state, and data exchange with other tools. Knowing file I/O lets you build utilities, store program output, and load input for batch processing. Correct error handling and closing streams prevents data corruption and resource exhaustion. \n## How it works \n1. Open a stream with `fopen(filename, mode)` where `mode` is \"r\", \"w\", \"a\", etc. Check the returned `FILE*` for `NULL` to detect failure. \n2. Write data using `fwrite`, `fprintf`, or `fputs`. For `fwrite`, check its return (a `size_t` count) to ensure all bytes were written. \n3. Read data using `fread`, `fgets`, or `fscanf`. For text, `fgets` reads a line safely into a buffer. \n4. Close the stream with `fclose`; always check its return when finishing critical writes. \nExample steps in this lesson\'s program: \n- Open a file for writing and write a text block using `fwrite`. \n- Close the file and report the number of bytes written. \n- Reopen the file for reading and print each line with `fgets`. \n- Close the file again. \n## Common mistakes \n- Not checking `fopen` return: if it returns `NULL`, subsequent calls crash; always handle the error and exit or retry. \n- Ignoring write/read return values: `fwrite`/`fread` return counts; partial writes can occur and should be handled. \n- Forgetting to `fclose` after writing: buffered data may not flush to disk until `fclose`, causing data loss. Fixes: always check return values and close files in all code paths. \n\n## Summary \n- Use `fopen`/`fclose` to manage file streams and always check for `NULL` and errors. \n- Use `fwrite`/`fread` for binary blocks and `fgets`/`fprintf` for text operations. \n- Check return values (`size_t` or `NULL`) to detect partial operations. \n- Always close files to flush buffers and release resources.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/io/fopen\n\n- https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/io/fwrite\n\nExample:\n\n```#include <stdio.h>\n#include <string.h>\n\nint main(void)\n{\n    const char* filename = \"sample.txt\";\n\nFILE* fp = fopen(filename, \"w\");\n    if (fp == NULL) return 1;\n\nconst char* msg = \"Line1\\n\";\n    fwrite(msg, 1, strlen(msg), fp);\n    fclose(fp);\n\nreturn 0;\n}\n```\n',NULL,1,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-21 16:53:47',NULL,'c'),('3c360637-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c317fc8-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Create a Command-Line Utility in C','mixed',1,'Build a small CLI tool that parses `argc/argv`, reads from files or `stdin`, and emits formatted output. This lesson shows why combining input sources matters for real utilities and walks through file handling, error reporting, and predictable output formatting. Watch for buffer limits, newline handling, and correct `FILE*` usage╪╕┬胂ⰀⰥ理栀攀猀攀