\nprint_list(head, \"Demo: \");\n\nfree_list(head);\n\nreturn 0;\n}\n```\n\n','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njTh_OwMljA',3,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-21 16:59:13',NULL,'c'),('3c38dc50-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3c317fc8-5478-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Test, Debug, and Optimize C Programs','mixed',1,'Learn to write simple tests, use debugging tools, and profile C code to find hotspots; fix bugs and apply safe micro-optimizations. This lesson shows practical techniques, common pitfalls (like premature or unsafe optimization), and demonstrates a deterministic test harness to verify correctness before optimizing. Avoid relying on timing alone and always validate behavior with reproducible tests.','## What is test, debug, and optimize \nThis lesson teaches how to combine **unit-like tests**, debugging tools, and simple profiling to find bugs and hotspots in C programs, then apply small, safe optimizations. We use repeatable tests to verify correctness before changing code, use a debugger to inspect state, and use counters or profilers to identify slow paths. \n## Why it matters \nReal C programs can be fragile: a small bug or undefined behavior can cause crashes or subtle data corruption. Profiling and simple tests ensure fixes are correct and optimizations target real bottlenecks rather than imaginary ones. This reduces regressions and wasted effort. \n## How it works \n1. Create a deterministic test that checks function outputs against expected values using predictable inputs (no timing measurements as single truth). \n2. Use a debugger (like `gdb`) to inspect variables and trace control flow when tests fail. \n3. Add inexpensive counters or use a profiler (e.g., `valgrind` or `perf`) to measure how often functions or loops run and locate hotspots. \n4. Apply safe micro-optimizations: reduce work inside hot loops, prefer pointer arithmetic carefully, and avoid premature complexity. \nExample test approach (conceptual): \n- Build test data with known result. \n- Run two implementations (e.g., index-based and pointer-based). \n- Compare outputs; only optimize when results match and counters show a real hotspot. \n## Common mistakes \n- Over-optimizing before correctness: always write tests first and ensure behavior is correct. Fix: create deterministic tests and run them after changes. \n- Trusting timing noise: system timers fluctuate; use counters or repeated runs, and prefer profiling tools for reliable hotspots. \n- Unsafe micro-optimizations: changing data access patterns can introduce undefined behavior; fix by keeping pointer bounds and correct types. \n## Summary \n- Write repeatable tests to verify correctness before optimizing. \n- Use a debugger to inspect state and locate logic bugs. \n- Use counters or profilers to find real hotspots, not guesses. \n- Apply small, safe changes inside hot loops and re-run tests to ensure no regressions.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://www.gnu.org/software/gdb/documentation/\n\n- https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Optimize-Options.html\n\nExample:\n\n```#include <stdio.h>\n\nlong sum_with_index(int *a, size_t n)\n{\n    long s = 0;\n\nfor (size_t i = 0; i < n; ++i)\n    {\n        s += a[i];\n    }\n\nreturn s;\n}\n\n/* A small test can call this and compare results from another implementation. */\n```\n\n',NULL,4,15,1,'2026-05-20 21:18:00','2026-05-21 17:01:13',NULL,'c'),('3ea1e149-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3e9eefdb-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Demonstrate Python Data Types and Constructs for Algorithms','mixed',1,'Show how to use Python **lists**, **sets**, **dictionaries**, comprehensions, and functions to filter, deduplicate, and count. Demonstrates why `set` membership is O(1) average and avoids O(n^2) `list` scans. Includes concise patterns, a runnable example, and an exercise. Pitfall: using `list.count()` or repeated `in` checks on lists causes slow O(n^2) behavior.','# # What is Python data types and constructs for algorithmic tasks This lesson demonstrates using **lists** , **sets** , and **dictionaries** together with `for` loops and comprehensions to implement common algorithmic building blocks: **filtering** , **deduplication** , and **frequency counting** . You will see how to preserve order when needed and how to get O(n) behavior using `set` membership and single-pass counting into a `dict` . # # Why it matters Efficient membership checks and counts are central to many algorithms (hashing, frequency analysis, graph adjacency cleanup). Using the right built-in types reduces complexity from O(n^2) to O(n) in typical cases. This matters for large inputs where algorithmic complexity dominates constant factors. # # How it works 1. Use `set` for O(1) average membership tests instead of scanning a `list` repeatedly. 2. Build a `dict` in a single pass to accumulate frequencies rather than calling `list.count()` inside loops. 3. If you need a deterministic order for unique items, produce a `sorted` or preserve first-seen order using a `set` to track seen elements. Example pattern to preserve first occurrence while deduplicating: ``` # preserve order while removing duplicates seen = set() unique_in_order = [] for x in items: if x not in seen: seen.add(x) unique_in_order.append(x) ``` # # Common mistakes 1. Using `if x in my_list` inside a loop to check membership leads to O(n^2) behavior; fix by using a `set` for membership checks. 2. Calling `list.count(x)` inside a loop causes repeated scans; fix by building a single-pass frequency `dict` with `counts[x] = counts.get(x, 0) + 1` . 3. Assuming `set` preserves insertion order ╪╕┬胂ⰀⰥ 甀猀攀 怀猀漀爀琀攀搀⠀⤀怀 漀爀 洀愀椀渀琀愀椀渀 愀 怀猀攀攀渀怀 猀攀琀 眀椀琀栀 愀渀 漀甀琀瀀甀琀 氀椀猀琀 眀栀攀渀 漀爀搀攀爀 洀愀琀琀攀爀猀⸀ ⌀ ⌀ 匀甀洀洀愀爀礀 ⴀ ⨀⨀唀猀攀 怀猀攀琀怀 ⨀⨀ 昀漀爀 愀瘀攀爀愀最攀 伀⠀㄀⤀ 洀攀洀戀攀爀猀栀椀瀀 挀栀攀挀欀猀⸀ ⴀ ⨀⨀䈀甀椀氀搀 愀 怀搀椀挀琀怀 椀渀 漀渀攀 瀀愀猀猀⨀⨀ 昀漀爀 昀爀攀焀甀攀渀挀礀 挀漀甀渀琀猀⸀ ⴀ ⨀⨀倀爀攀猀攀爀瘀攀 漀爀搀攀爀⨀⨀ 戀礀 琀爀愀挀欀椀渀最 怀猀攀攀渀怀 攀氀攀洀攀渀琀猀 漀爀 猀漀爀琀椀渀最 甀渀椀焀甀攀 瘀愀氀甀攀猀⸀ ⴀ ⨀⨀䄀瘀漀椀搀 爀攀瀀攀愀琀攀搀 怀氀椀猀琀怀 猀挀愀渀猀⨀⨀ 猀甀挀栀 愀猀 怀氀椀猀琀⸀挀漀甀渀琀⠀⤀怀 椀渀猀椀搀攀 氀漀漀瀀猀⸀尀渀尀渀唀猀攀昀甀氀 刀攀猀漀甀爀挀攀猀㨀尀渀尀渀ⴀ 栀琀琀瀀猀㨀⼀⼀搀漀挀猀⸀瀀礀琀栀漀渀⸀漀爀最⼀㌀⼀