ter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, val):\n        self.val = val\n        self.next = None\n\nclass LinkedList:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.head = None\n\n    def add(self, val):\n        if not self.head:\n            self.head = Node(val)\n            return\n\n        cur = self.head\n        while cur.next:\n            cur = cur.next\n        cur.next = Node(val)\n\n    def print_list(self):\n        cur = self.head\n        while cur:\n            print(cur.val, end=\" \")\n            cur = cur.next\n        print()\n\nll = LinkedList()\nll.add(1)\nll.add(2)\nll.add(3)\n\nll.print_list()\n}}\n\n{{answer: 1 2 3 }}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G0_I-ZF0S38',4,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 19:43:35',NULL,'python'),('3eb0b947-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3ea8e225-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Optimize Sequence Operations and Explain Amortized Analysis','mixed',1,'Show how to implement and reason about amortized costs for dynamic arrays (Python lists). Learn why `append` is usually O(1) amortized, how doubling resizing works, and a common pitfall: counting worst-case copies for every operation instead of amortized totals.','# # What is amortized analysis **Amortized analysis ** measures the average cost per operation over a sequence of operations, rather than the worst case of a single operation. For dynamic arrays, we count the total work (including occasional costly resizes) and divide by the number of operations to get the ** amortized ** cost. # # Why it matters Understanding amortized cost explains why Python\'s `list.append` is effectively ** O(1) amortized **, even though a resize step can be O(n). This matters when designing algorithms that perform many appends: you can treat each append as constant-time for complexity analysis. # # How it works 1. Start with a small capacity (e.g., 1). 2. On each `append` , if the array is full, allocate a new array with larger capacity (commonly double), copy existing elements, then append the new element. 3. Resizes are rare: doubling causes the total number of copies after N appends to be O(N). Dividing total copies by N gives O(1) amortized per append. Example intuition: when capacity doubles from 8 to 16, you copy 8 elements once; those 8 copies \\\"pay for\\\" many subsequent appends. # # Common mistakes - Assuming every `append` is O(n): this is the worst-case for a single append during resize, but not the amortized cost; compute the total copies across many appends instead. - Forgetting initial capacity edge cases: starting capacity 0 vs 1 changes where the first resize happens; model initial capacity clearly. - Mixing cost metrics: be explicit whether you count element copies, allocations, or CPU time. # # Summary - ** Amortized analysis ** averages cost over sequences, not single operations. - Dynamic arrays resize rarely; doubling keeps total copies O(N). - `append` is ** O(1) amortized**, but sometimes O(n) in the worst case. - When analyzing algorithms, use amortized costs for repeated sequence operations. ```python # Simple simulation of a dynamic array\'s doubling behavior for N inserts # This snippet is for illustration and uses the same resizing model used in the lesson class SimpleSim: def __init__(self): self.size = 0 self.capacity = 1 def will_resize_on_next(self): return self.size == self.capacity sim = SimpleSim() for i in range(8): if sim.will_resize_on_next(): sim.capacity *= 2 sim.size += 1 print(sim.size, sim.capacity) ```\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/datastructures.html#more-on-lists\n\n- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amortized_analysis\n\n- https://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/4731/how-does-doubling-resize-lead-to-amortized-constant-time-append\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5o-kdjv7FD0}}\n\nExample:\n\n```# example: run 20 appends to see how resizes scale\n\nclass DynamicArrayExample:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.size = 0\n        self.capacity = 1\n        self.resizes = 0\n        self.total_copies = 0\n\ndef append(self, value):\n        if self.size == self.capacity:\n            self.total_copies += self.size\n            self.capacity *= 2\n            self.resizes += 1\n\nself.size += 1\n\narr = DynamicArrayExample()\nfor i in range(20):\n    arr.append(i)\n\nprint(arr.size, arr.capacity, arr.resizes, arr.total_copies)\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nclass DynamicArrayExample:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.size = 0\n        self.capacity = 1\n        self.resizes = 0\n        self.total_copies = 0\n\n    def append(self, value):\n        if self.size == self.capacity:\n            self.total_copies += self.size\n            self.capacity *= 2\n            self.resizes += 1\n\n        self.size += 1\n\n\narr = DynamicArrayExample()\n\nfor i in range(20):\n    arr.append(i)\n\nprint(arr.size, arr.capacity, arr.resizes, arr.total_copies)\n}}\n\n{{answer: 20 32 5 31}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5o-kdjv7FD0',5,12,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 19:46:21',NULL,'python'),('3eb2b548-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3eb1ad1b-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Define Hash Tables and Python dict Behavior','mixed',1,'Introduce hashing, why collisions occur, basic resolution strategies, and how Python\'s `dict` implements a high-performance hash table. Covers chaining vs open addressing, resizing trade-offs, and a compact Python example that forces collisions. Watch for pitfalls: relying on string hash stability across runs and confusing bucket storage with key order.','## What is hashing **Hashing** is a process that maps input values (keys) to integer indices (hashes) used to place items into a fixed-size table. A **hash table** stores key-value pairs and uses a hash function to determine which bucket or slot a key belongs to. ## Why it matters Hash tables provide average-case **O(1)** time for insertions, lookups, and deletions, making them essential for fast indexing, caches, symbol tables, and many algorithmic optimizations. Understanding collisions and resolution affects performance and correctness. ## How it works 1. Compute a hash from the key (often an integer or the result of `hash(key)`). 2. Map the hash to an index via modulo or bitmasking onto the table capacity. 3. Place the `(key, value)` pair into that bucket or probe for an open slot. 4. On lookup, compute the same index and search the bucket or follow the probing sequence. Python\'s built-in `dict` implements a tuned **open addressing** scheme (with perturbation and probe sequences) plus automatic resizing. It stores entries in contiguous arrays for great cache locality and uses special markers for deleted slots. When load factor grows, `dict` resizes to maintain speed. ## Common mistakes - Assuming `hash(str)` is stable across interpreter runs: Python randomizes string hashes by default, so don\'t rely on cross-process hash values; use integers for deterministic examples. - Confusing bucket order with insertion order: a plain hash table\'s internal bucket arrangement is unrelated to insertion order; Python 3.7+ preserves insertion order at the `dict` API level, but that is a separate guarantee layered on top of the hash table internals. - Using a too-small capacity without resizing: this increases collisions and degrades performance; implement resizing or rely on `dict` which resizes automatically. ## Summary - **Hashing** maps keys to table indices for fast access. - **Collisions** occur when different keys map to the same index; resolve with **chaining** or **open addressing**. - **Python `dict`** uses an optimized open-addressing scheme with resizing for average O(1) performance. - For deterministic examples, use integer keys and be mindful of load factors. ```python # Example: simple chaining-based hash table to demonstrate collisions class HashTable: def __init__(self, capacity=3): self.capacity = capacity self.buckets = [[] for _ in range(capacity)] def put(self, key, value): idx = key % self.capacity self.buckets[idx].append((key, value)) def get(self, key): idx = key % self.capacity for k, v in self.buckets[idx]: if k == key: return v return None ht = HashTable(3) ht.put(1, \'one\') ht.put(4, \'four\') # collides with 1 when capacity is 3 print(ht.buckets) print(ht.get(4)) ```\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#mapping-types-dict\n\n- https://realpython.com/python-dicts/\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=daefaLgNkw0}}\n\nExample:\n\n```class HashTable:\n    def __init__(self, capacity=3):\n        self.capacity = capacity\n        self.buckets = [[] for _ in range(capacity)]\n\ndef put(self, key, value):\n        idx = key % self.capacity\n        self.buckets[idx].append((key, value))\n\nht = HashTable(3)\nht.put(1, \'one\')\nht.put(4, \'four\')  # 1 and 4 collide when capacity is 3\nprint(ht.buckets)\nprint(ht.buckets[1])\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nclass HashTable:\n    def __init__(self, capacity=3):\n        self.capacity = capacity\n        self.buckets = [[] for _ in range(capacity)]\n\n    def put(self, key, value):\n        index = key % self.capacity\n        self.buckets[index].append((key, value))\n\n\nht = HashTable(3)\n\nht.put(1, \"one\")\nht.put(4, \"four\")\nht.put(7, \"seven\")\n\nprint(ht.buckets)\nprint(ht.buckets[1])\n}}\n\n{{answer: [[], [(1, \'one\'), (4, \'four\'), (7, \'seven\')], []]\n[(1, \'one\'), (4, \'four\'), (7, \'seven\')]}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=daefaLgNkw0',1,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 19:47:48',NULL,'python'),('3eb90ff3-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3eb1ad1b-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Demonstrate Heaps and Priority Queues with heapq','mixed',1,'Show how to use Python\'s `heapq` to implement min- and max-priority queues, perform `heappush`/`heappop`, and convert lists to heaps. Learn why heaps are efficient for repeated smallest/largest extraction and a common pitfall: `heapq` is a min-heap only, so implement max-heaps by negating values. Watch out for in-place `heapify` modifying the original list.','## What is a Heap and Priority Queue A **heap** is a specialized binary tree that satisfies the heap property: each parent node is <= (min-heap) or >= (max-heap) its children. A **priority queue** uses a heap to return the highest-priority item quickly. In Python, `heapq` provides a fast min-heap implementation via a list. ## Why it matters Heaps give O(log n) insertion and removal for priority operations, which is far better than sorting repeatedly. They are used in algorithms like Dijkstra\'s shortest paths, event simulation, and scheduling. ## How it works - Use `heapq.heapify(list)` to transform a list into a heap in O(n) time. - Use `heapq.heappush(heap, item)` to add an item in O(log n). - Use `heapq.heappop(heap)` to remove and return the smallest item in O(log n). `heapq` is a **min-heap** only; implement a max-heap by storing negated values and negating back on pop. Example: ```python import heapq vals = [3, 1, 4] min_h = vals[:] heapq.heapify(min_h) heapq.heappush(min_h, 0) print([heapq.heappop(min_h) for _ in range(len(min_h))]) max_h = [-v for v in vals] heapq.heapify(max_h) heapq.heappush(max_h, -5) print([-heapq.heappop(max_h) for _ in range(len(max_h))]) ``` ## Common mistakes - Assuming `heapq` supports a max-heap: fix by negating values on insert/pop. - Forgetting that `heapify` mutates the list: avoid reusing the original list or copy it first. - Expecting O(1) arbitrary deletions: `heapq` does not efficiently delete arbitrary elements; use lazy deletion or another structure. ## Summary - **heapq** provides a fast min-heap using Python lists. - Use `heapify`, `heappush`, and `heappop` for O(n) build and O(log n) updates. - Implement max-heap by negating values. - Heaps are ideal for repeated min/max extraction tasks like scheduling and shortest paths.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://docs.python.org/3/library/heapq.html\n\n- https://realpython.com/python-heapq-module/\n\n\nExample:\n\n```import heapq\n\n# Simple example: min-heap\nh = [3, 1, 4]\nheapq.heapify(h)\nheapq.heappush(h, 0)\nprint(heapq.heappop(h))  # prints 0\n\n# Max-heap via negation\nmh = [-x for x in [3, 1, 4]]\nheapq.heapify(mh)\nheapq.heappush(mh, -5)\nprint(-heapq.heappop(mh))  # prints 5\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nimport heapq\n\n# Starter list of numbers\nnums = [5, 1, 3, 2, 8]\n\n# -------- Min Heap --------\nmin_heap = nums[:]\nheapq.heapify(min_heap)\nheapq.heappush(min_heap, 0)\n\nsmallest = heapq.heappop(min_heap)\nnext_smallest = heapq.heappop(min_heap)\n\nprint(\"Min-heap popped:\", smallest, next_smallest)\n\n# -------- Max Heap --------\nmax_heap = [-n for n in nums]\nheapq.heapify(max_heap)\nheapq.heappush(max_heap, -7)\n\nlargest = -heapq.heappop(max_heap)\nnext_largest = -heapq.heappop(max_heap)\n\nprint(\"Max-heap popped:\", largest, next_largest)\n}}\n\n{{answer:Min-heap popped: 0 1\nMax-heap popped: 8 7}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F2JCjVSZlG0',2,12,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 19:52:24',NULL,'python'),('3eba3830-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3eb1ad1b-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Apply Binary Trees: Implement Traversals and Recursive Operations','mixed',1,'Implement a binary tree node and write recursive pre-order, in-order, and post-order traversals in Python. Learn how to return traversal lists, combine subtree results, and analyze runtime and space complexity. This lesson teaches practical recursive patterns for tree operations and warns against common pitfalls such as missing base cases or reusing a single mutable list across recursive calls, which produces incorrect traversal outputs.','## What is a binary tree traversal A **binary tree traversal** is a systematic way to visit every node in a binary tree. Common orders are **pre-order** (`root, left, right`), **in-order** (`left, root, right`), and **post-order** (`left, right, root`). Each traversal can be implemented with simple recursion that returns a list of visited node values. ## Why it matters Tree traversals are fundamental to many algorithms: expression evaluation, tree serialization, search helpers, and many LeetCode-style problems. Knowing how to implement traversals cleanly and return results makes tree-based problem solving straightforward and testable. ## How it works Each recursive traversal follows the same pattern: handle the **base case** (`None` returns an empty list), then combine results from subcalls in the required order. Returning new lists from each call avoids shared-mutable-list bugs and makes reasoning about complexity clear. Example implementation (small tree): ```python class Node: def __init__(self, val, left=None, right=None): self.val = val self.left = left self.right = right def preorder(node): if not node: return [] return [node.val] + preorder(node.left) + preorder(node.right) # build tree: 1 with children 2 and 3 root = Node(1, Node(2), Node(3)) print(preorder(root)) # -> [1, 2, 3] ``` ## Common mistakes - Missing the base case: forgetting `if not node: return []` results in exceptions or infinite recursion; always include it. - Reusing a single list across recursive calls: appending into a shared list argument can mix results from sibling calls; instead, return new lists and combine. - Confusing traversal order: draw the tree and step through a small example to verify the order before generalizing. ## Summary - Use **recursion** with a clear base case for binary tree traversals. - Prefer returning new lists from recursive calls and combining them rather than mutating a shared list. - Pre-order: `root, left, right`; In-order: `left, root, right`; Post-order: `left, right, root`. - Analyze runtime as **O(n)** for traversals and space **O(h)** for recursion stack (where `h` is tree height).\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://realpython.com/binary-tree-python/\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6oL-0TdVy28}}\n\nExample:\n\n```class Node:\n    def __init__(self, val, left=None, right=None):\n        self.val = val\n        self.left = left\n        self.right = right\n\ndef preorder(node):\n    if not node:\n        return []\n    return [node.val] + preorder(node.left) + preorder(node.right)\n\n# small example tree\nroot = Node(1, Node(2), Node(3))\nprint(preorder(root))  # -> [1, 2, 3]\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, val):\n        self.val = val\n        self.left = None\n        self.right = None\n\ndef preorder(node):\n    if node is None:\n        return []\n\n    return [node.val] + preorder(node.left) + preorder(node.right)\n\n# example tree\n#      1\n#     / \\\n#    2   3\n\nroot = Node(1)\nroot.left = Node(2)\nroot.right = Node(3)\n\nprint(preorder(root))\n}}\n\n{{answer: [1, 2, 3]}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6oL-0TdVy28',3,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 19:53:34',NULL,'python'),('3ebb2eb0-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3eb1ad1b-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Handle Binary Search Trees: Insert, Delete, and Degenerate Cases','mixed',1,'Implement BST `insert`, `delete`, and `search` in Python, handling duplicates and skewed (degenerate) trees. Learn why correct deletion cases (leaf, one child, two children) matter for correctness and complexity, and avoid common pitfalls like mishandling inorder successor or allowing silent duplicates that corrupt structure.','## What is BST insert/delete/search A **Binary Search Tree (BST)** is a binary tree where for every node, all keys in the left subtree are less than the node key and all keys in the right subtree are greater. `insert` places a new value preserving BST order, `search` locates a key, and `delete` removes a key while maintaining structure. ## Why it matters BST operations are fundamental building blocks for ordered collections and many algorithms (set/map implementations, search optimizations). Correct deletion is crucial: mishandling the three deletion cases can corrupt the tree and degrade performance to linear time in degenerate (skewed) trees. ## How it works 1. `insert`: recurse down left/right following comparisons and attach a new node at a null child. 2. `search`: recurse left or right based on comparisons until found or reached null. 3. `delete`: handle three cases: - **Leaf**: simply remove the node. - **One child**: replace the node with its non-null child. - **Two children**: find the node\'s inorder successor (smallest node in right subtree), copy its value to the node, then delete the successor node from the right subtree. Use `inorder` traversal to verify tree integrity since it yields sorted keys for BSTs. ## Common mistakes - Forgetting to return the updated subtree root after recursion, which breaks parent links; always return the subtree root. - Mishandling the two-child deletion by deleting the successor incorrectly; find the minimum in the right subtree and delete that exact node. - Allowing duplicates without a clear policy; either reject duplicates or define a convention (e.g., insert duplicates to the right) and apply it consistently. ## Summary - **insert**, **search**, and **delete** maintain BST invariants. - Deletion has three distinct cases (leaf, one child, two children); handle each explicitly. - Use `inorder` traversal to validate tree structure because it returns sorted keys. - Skewed insertions produce degenerate trees with O(n) operations; balance strategies are separate topics. ```python # Example: small BST insert and search class Node: def __init__(self, key): self.key = key self.left = None self.right = None def insert(root, key): if root is None: return Node(key) if key < root.key: root.left = insert(root.left, key) else: root.right = insert(root.right, key) return root root = None for k in [50, 30, 70, 20, 40]: root = insert(root, k) # Inorder should be sorted def inorder(root): return inorder(root.left) + [root.key] + inorder(root.right) if root else [] print(inorder(root)) ```\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://realpython.com/binary-search-tree-python/\n\nExample:\n\n```class Node:\n    def __init__(self, key):\n        self.key = key\n        self.left = None\n        self.right = None\n\ndef insert(root, key):\n    if root is None:\n        return Node(key)\n    if key < root.key:\n        root.left = insert(root.left, key)\n    else:\n        root.right = insert(root.right, key)\n    return root\n\nroot = None\nfor k in [5, 2, 8]:\n    root = insert(root, k)\n\nprint(inorder(root))\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, key):\n        self.key = key\n        self.left = None\n        self.right = None\n\n\ndef insert(root, key):\n    if root is None:\n        return Node(key)\n\n    if key < root.key:\n        root.left = insert(root.left, key)\n    else:\n        root.right = insert(root.right, key)\n\n    return root\n\n\ndef inorder(root):\n    if root is None:\n        return []\n\n    return inorder(root.left) + [root.key] + inorder(root.right)\n\n\nroot = None\nfor k in [5, 2, 8]:\n    root = insert(root, k)\n\nprint(inorder(root))\n}}\n\n{{answer: [2, 5, 8]}}',NULL,4,15,0,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 19:54:25',NULL,'python'),('3ec506ed-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3eb1ad1b-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Optimize Tree Structures: When to Use Balanced Trees or Heaps','mixed',1,'Compare heaps, plain BSTs, and balanced tree strategies to choose the best data structure for different workloads. Learn performance trade-offs for inserts, deletes, searches, and top-k operations, why unbalanced BSTs can degenerate, and when a heap is the simpler, faster choice. Watch for the common pitfall: using a heap for frequent arbitrary searches or an unbalanced BST when adversarial inserts are possible.','## What is a heap vs BST vs balanced tree A **heap** is a specialized tree-based data structure that guarantees fast access to the min/max element (`O(1)` peek, `O(log n)` push/pop) but does not support efficient arbitrary search or ordered traversal. A plain **Binary Search Tree (BST)** supports ordered traversal and `O(h)` search/insert/delete where `h` is tree height. A **balanced tree** (AVL/Red-Black) enforces `h = O(log n)`, guaranteeing `O(log n)` for these ops. ## Why it matters Choosing the right structure directly affects algorithm performance. Use a heap when you only need repeated access to the current min/max or for priority-based processing. Use a BST when you need ordered iteration or range queries. Use a balanced tree when you need both ordered operations and guaranteed logarithmic worst-case bounds. ## How it works 1. Heap: `heapq` in Python maintains the heap invariant; push/pop are `O(log n)`. Contains checks are `O(n)` because the heap is not ordered for arbitrary searches. 2. BST: insert and search traverse down from the root; average case is `O(log n)` for random data, but worst-case degrades to `O(n)` for sorted/adversarial inserts. 3. Balanced trees: rotations or color fixes happen on insert/delete to keep height `O(log n)`, preserving worst-case bounds╪╕┬胂ⰀⰥ瘆愀氀甀愀戀氀攀 椀渀 猀礀猀琀攀洀猀 眀椀琀栀 眀漀爀猀琀ⴀ挀愀猀攀 挀漀渀猀琀爀愀椀渀琀猀⸀ 䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀 ⠀搀攀洀漀渀猀琀爀愀琀椀漀渀⤀㨀 怀怀怀瀀礀琀栀漀渀 ⌀ 䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀 戀甀椀氀搀 愀 猀椀洀瀀氀攀 䈀匀吀 愀渀搀 愀 栀攀愀瀀 昀漀爀 琀栀攀 猀愀洀攀 搀愀琀愀 椀洀瀀漀爀琀 栀攀愀瀀焀 搀愀琀愀 㴀 嬀㜀Ⰰ㈀Ⰰ㤀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ㔀Ⰰ㠀Ⰰ㌀Ⰰ㘀Ⰰ㐀Ⰰ㄀　崀 ⌀ 䠀攀愀瀀㨀 瀀甀猀栀 愀氀氀Ⰰ 瀀攀攀欀 猀洀愀氀氀攀猀琀 栀攀愀瀀 㴀 嬀崀 昀漀爀 渀 椀渀 搀愀琀愀㨀 栀攀愀瀀焀⸀栀攀愀瀀瀀甀猀栀⠀栀攀愀瀀Ⰰ 渀⤀ ⌀ 匀椀洀瀀氀攀 甀渀戀愀氀愀渀挀攀搀 䈀匀吀 挀氀愀猀猀 䈀匀吀一漀搀攀㨀 搀攀昀 开开椀渀椀琀开开⠀猀攀氀昀Ⰰ 瘀愀氀⤀㨀 猀攀氀昀⸀瘀愀氀 㴀 瘀愀氀 猀攀氀昀⸀氀攀昀琀 㴀 一漀渀攀 猀攀氀昀⸀爀椀最栀琀 㴀 一漀渀攀 搀攀昀 椀渀猀攀爀琀⠀猀攀氀昀Ⰰ 瘀⤀㨀 椀昀 瘀 㰀 猀攀氀昀⸀瘀愀氀㨀 椀昀 猀攀氀昀⸀氀攀昀琀㨀 猀攀氀昀⸀氀攀昀琀⸀椀渀猀攀爀琀⠀瘀⤀ 攀氀猀攀㨀 猀攀氀昀⸀氀攀昀琀 㴀 䈀匀吀一漀搀攀⠀瘀⤀ 攀氀猀攀㨀 椀昀 猀攀氀昀⸀爀椀最栀琀㨀 猀攀氀昀⸀爀椀最栀琀⸀椀渀猀攀爀琀⠀瘀⤀ 攀氀猀攀㨀 猀攀氀昀⸀爀椀最栀琀 㴀 䈀匀吀一漀搀攀⠀瘀⤀ 搀攀昀 猀攀愀爀挀栀⠀猀攀氀昀Ⰰ 瘀⤀㨀 椀昀 瘀 㴀㴀 猀攀氀昀⸀瘀愀氀㨀 爀攀琀甀爀渀 吀爀甀攀 椀昀 瘀 㰀 猀攀氀昀⸀瘀愀氀㨀 爀攀琀甀爀渀 猀攀氀昀⸀氀攀昀琀⸀猀攀愀爀挀栀⠀瘀⤀ 椀昀 猀攀氀昀⸀氀攀昀琀 攀氀猀攀 䘀愀氀猀攀 爀攀琀甀爀渀 猀攀氀昀⸀