subgraphs. Fix: iterate all nodes and call DFS when unvisited. - Not detecting self-loops: an edge from a node to itself is a cycle. Fix: treat neighbors equally in the DFS and detect `visiting` state. - Attempting to topo-sort a graph with a cycle: this yields incorrect results rather than an error. Fix: check for cycles first and abort sorting if one exists. # # Summary - **Detect cycles** with DFS using three visitation states. - **Topological sort** uses DFS post-order reversed, but only for DAGs. - **Handle disconnected graphs** by iterating all nodes and starting DFS when needed. - **Check for self-loops and cycles** before trusting a topological order.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/topological-sorting/\n\n- https://cp-algorithms.com/graph/topological-sort.html\n\n- https://realpython.com/python-graphs-intro/\n\n\nExample:\n\n```# example: DFS-based topo sort on a DAG\n\ngraph = {\n    \'shirt\': [\'tie\', \'belt\'],\n    \'tie\': [\'jacket\'],\n    \'belt\': [\'jacket\'],\n    \'jacket\': []\n}\n\nvisited = set()\norder = []\n\ndef dfs(u):\n    visited.add(u)\n    for v in graph[u]:\n        if v not in visited:\n            dfs(v)\n    order.append(u)\n\nfor node in graph:\n    if node not in visited:\n        dfs(node)\n\norder.reverse()\nprint(order)\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\ngraph = {\n    \'shirt\': [\'tie\', \'belt\'],\n    \'tie\': [\'jacket\'],\n    \'belt\': [\'jacket\'],\n    \'jacket\': []\n}\n\nvisited = set()\nresult = []\n\ndef dfs(node):\n    if node in visited:\n        return\n\n    visited.add(node)\n\n    for neighbor in graph[node]:\n        dfs(neighbor)\n\n    result.append(node)\n\nfor node in graph:\n    dfs(node)\n\nprint(result[::-1])\n}}\n\n{{answer: [\'shirt\', \'belt\', \'tie\', \'jacket\']}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ddTC4Z0GLk',4,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 20:08:45',NULL,'python'),('3ecad780-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3ec5d05d-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Optimize Graph Algorithms for Sparse vs Dense Graphs','mixed',1,'Learn to analyze graph density and pick the best representation and algorithm to minimize time and memory. We\'ll compare adjacency lists vs matrices for neighbor iteration and edge-existence queries, explain when each shines, and highlight a common pitfall: choosing a structure without matching it to the operations required.','## What is graph representation optimization Graph representation optimization is choosing the most suitable internal structure (for example, **adjacency list** or **adjacency matrix**) and algorithm based on the graph\'s **density** and the operations you need to perform, such as neighbor iteration or many edge-existence queries. ## Why it matters Picking the wrong representation wastes time and memory: an adjacency matrix uses O(n^2) memory and is often wasteful for sparse graphs, while an adjacency list provides faster neighbor iteration for sparse graphs but slower edge-existence checks. Choosing appropriately directly improves runtime for real-world problems like routing, social graphs, and pathfinding. ## How it works 1. Measure density: compute edges E and nodes n; density ~ 2E / (n(n-1)) for undirected graphs. 2. Compare costs for the operations you need: - Neighbor iteration: adjacency list cost ~ O(sum of degrees) = O(2E); adjacency matrix cost ~ O(n^2) to scan row entries. - Edge-existence queries: adjacency list average check ~ O(degree) (worst O(n)), adjacency matrix check = O(1). 3. Make the trade-off decision: - If E << n^2 (sparse) and your workload iterates neighbors frequently, prefer **adjacency list**. - If the graph is dense or you perform many edge-existence queries/need constant-time edge lookups, prefer **adjacency matrix** or hybrid approaches. Example code below demonstrates measuring these costs in Python. ## Common mistakes - Assuming adjacency matrix is always faster: this ignores memory and neighbor-iteration cost; for sparse large n it is often slower and memory-heavy. Fix: compute n and E and estimate operations required before choosing. - Using adjacency list for heavy random edge-existence workloads without indexing: fix by using a `set` for neighbor lists or a matrix for O(1) checks. ## Summary - Choose representation based on **operations** (neighbor iteration vs edge existence) and **density**. - Adjacency list is usually best for sparse graphs and neighbor traversal. - Adjacency matrix provides O(1) edge checks but costs O(n^2) memory. - When in doubt, measure expected costs (degrees vs n^2) for your actual workload. ```python # Example: compute costs for a dense-ish graph and compare n = 8 edges = [(i, j) for i in range(n) for j in range(i+1, n)] # near-complete # build adjacency list adj = {i: [] for i in range(n)} for u, v in edges: adj[u].append(v) adj[v].append(u) # neighbor iteration cost (list) and matrix scan cost list_checks = sum(len(adj[i]) for i in range(n)) matrix_checks = n * n print(\"Adjacency list neighbor checks:\", list_checks) print(\"Adjacency matrix neighbor checks:\", matrix_checks) ```\n\n\nExample:\n\n```n = 6\nedges = [(0,1), (0,2), (1,2), (2,3), (3,4), (4,5), (1,5)]\n\nadj = {i: [] for i in range(n)}\nfor u, v in edges:\n    adj[u].append(v)\n    adj[v].append(u)\n\nlist_checks = sum(len(adj[i]) for i in range(n))\nmatrix_checks = n * n\n\nprint(\"Adjacency list neighbor checks:\", list_checks)\nprint(\"Adjacency matrix neighbor checks:\", matrix_checks)\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nn = 5\nedges = [(0,1), (0,3), (1,2), (1,4), (3,4)]\n\nadj = {i: [] for i in range(n)}\nfor u, v in edges:\n    adj[u].append(v)\n    adj[v].append(u)\n\nlist_checks = sum(len(adj[i]) for i in range(n))\nmatrix_checks = n * n\n\nprint(\"Adjacency list neighbor checks:\", list_checks)\nprint(\"Adjacency matrix neighbor checks:\", matrix_checks)\n}}\n\n{{answer:Adjacency list neighbor checks: 10\nAdjacency matrix neighbor checks: 25}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oDqjPvD54Ss',5,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 20:10:09',NULL,'python'),('3ecc8a6a-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3ecc364e-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Define Algorithm Design Patterns for Problem Solving','mixed',1,'Learn the core algorithmic design patterns ╪╕┬胂ⰀⰥ 猀氀椀搀椀渀最 眀椀渀搀漀眀Ⰰ 琀眀漀ⴀ瀀漀椀渀琀攀爀猀Ⰰ 搀椀瘀椀搀攀ⴀ愀渀搀ⴀ挀漀渀焀甀攀爀Ⰰ 最爀攀攀搀礀Ⰰ 愀渀搀 搀礀渀愀洀椀挀 瀀爀漀最爀愀洀洀椀渀最 樀唥Ⱕ숥┬ج so you can pick a pattern to match problem constraints. Understand when each pattern is appropriate, why it reduces complexity, and a common pitfall: choosing the wrong pattern increases time or space costs. See a practical sliding-window example and a starter exercise to implement it.','## What is algorithm design patterns Algorithm design patterns are reusable strategies that solve broad classes of problems. Examples include **sliding window**, **two-pointers**, **divide-and-conquer**, **greedy**, and **dynamic programming**. Each pattern prescribes a structure and common steps to transform a problem into an efficient algorithm. ## Why it matters Patterns let you recognize the right approach quickly and avoid reinventing solutions. Choosing the correct pattern often converts an impractical brute-force O(n^2) solution into an efficient O(n) or O(n log n) solution. ## How it works - **Sliding window**: maintain a window (range) over a sequence and update its value incrementally when the window moves. Best when you need aggregates over contiguous elements (max/min/sum). - **Two-pointers**: use two indices moving at different rates or directions to solve sorted-array or pair-sum problems without extra memory. - **Divide-and-conquer**: split the problem into subproblems, solve recursively, and combine results (e.g., merge sort, quicksort). - **Greedy**: make the locally optimal choice at each step when it leads to a global optimum (e.g., activity selection). - **Dynamic programming**: store overlapping subproblem results to avoid recomputation; use when optimal substructure and overlapping subproblems are present. ## Common mistakes - Picking **greedy** when the problem lacks a greedy-choice property; fix: verify optimal substructure first. - Using brute-force instead of **sliding window** for contiguous subarray aggregates; fix: compute initial window then update incrementally to O(n). - Excessive recursion depth with **divide-and-conquer**; fix: convert to iterative or ensure balanced splits. ## Summary - Recognize patterns by problem shape: contiguous ╪╕┬蛂᠀別 ⨀⨀猀氀椀搀椀渀最 眀椀渀搀漀眀⨀⨀㬀 琀眀漀ⴀ椀渀搀攀砀 挀漀渀猀琀爀愀椀渀琀猀 樀唥Ⱕ숥┘ْ **two-pointers**. - Patterns reduce complexity: many transform O(n^2) to O(n) or O(n log n). - Validate correctness: check invariants (window boundaries, pointer movement, DP states). - Practice by implementing small pattern-based functions; this lesson╪╕┬胂樀⨥猆 攀砀愀洀瀀氀攀 搀攀洀漀渀猀琀爀愀琀攀猀 琀栀攀 ⨀⨀猀氀椀搀椀渀最 眀椀渀搀漀眀⨀⨀ 琀漀 昀椀渀搀 琀栀攀 洀愀砀椀洀甀洀 猀甀洀 漀昀 愀 昀椀砀攀搀ⴀ猀椀稀攀 猀甀戀愀爀爀愀礀⸀ 怀怀怀瀀礀琀栀漀渀 ⌀ 䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀 猀氀椀搀椀渀最 眀椀渀搀漀眀 ⴀ 椀洀瀀氀攀洀攀渀琀攀搀 昀甀渀挀琀椀漀渀 搀攀昀 洀愀砀开猀甀戀愀爀爀愀礀开猀甀洀开欀⠀愀爀爀Ⰰ 欀⤀㨀 椀昀 欀 㰀㴀 　 漀爀 欀 㸀 氀攀渀⠀愀爀爀⤀㨀 爀攀琀甀爀渀 　 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 㴀 猀甀洀⠀愀爀爀嬀㨀欀崀⤀ 洀愀砀椀洀甀洀 㴀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 昀漀爀 椀 椀渀 爀愀渀最攀⠀欀Ⰰ 氀攀渀⠀愀爀爀⤀⤀㨀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 ⬀㴀 愀爀爀嬀椀崀 ⴀ 愀爀爀嬀椀 ⴀ 欀崀 椀昀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 㸀 洀愀砀椀洀甀洀㨀 洀愀砀椀洀甀洀 㴀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 爀攀琀甀爀渀 洀愀砀椀洀甀洀 瀀爀椀渀琀⠀尀∀䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀 洀愀砀 猀甀洀 昀漀爀 欀㴀㌀㨀尀∀Ⰰ 洀愀砀开猀甀戀愀爀爀愀礀开猀甀洀开欀⠀嬀㈀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ㔀Ⰰ㄀Ⰰ㌀Ⰰ㈀崀Ⰰ ㌀⤀⤀ 怀怀怀尀渀尀渀唀猀攀昀甀氀 刀攀猀漀甀爀挀攀猀㨀尀渀尀渀ⴀ 栀琀琀瀀猀㨀⼀⼀爀攀愀氀瀀礀琀栀漀渀⸀挀漀洀⼀愀氀最漀爀椀琀栀洀椀挀ⴀ琀栀椀渀欀椀渀最⼀尀渀尀渀䔀砀愀洀瀀氀攀㨀尀渀尀渀怀怀怀搀攀昀 洀愀砀开猀甀戀愀爀爀愀礀开猀甀洀开欀⠀愀爀爀Ⰰ 欀⤀㨀尀渀    椀昀 欀 㰀㴀 　 漀爀 欀 㸀 氀攀渀⠀愀爀爀⤀㨀尀渀        爀攀琀甀爀渀 　尀渀尀渀挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 㴀 猀甀洀⠀愀爀爀嬀㨀欀崀⤀尀渀    洀愀砀椀洀甀洀 㴀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀尀渀尀渀昀漀爀 椀 椀渀 爀愀渀最攀⠀欀Ⰰ 氀攀渀⠀愀爀爀⤀⤀㨀尀渀        挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 ⬀㴀 愀爀爀嬀椀崀 ⴀ 愀爀爀嬀椀 ⴀ 欀崀尀渀        椀昀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 㸀 洀愀砀椀洀甀洀㨀尀渀            洀愀砀椀洀甀洀 㴀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀尀渀尀渀爀攀琀甀爀渀 洀愀砀椀洀甀洀尀渀尀渀瀀爀椀渀琀⠀洀愀砀开猀甀戀愀爀爀愀礀开猀甀洀开欀⠀嬀㈀Ⰰ ㄀Ⰰ 㔀Ⰰ ㄀Ⰰ ㌀Ⰰ ㈀崀Ⰰ ㌀⤀⤀尀渀怀怀怀尀渀尀渀䰀椀瘀攀 䌀漀搀椀渀最 吀愀猀欀㨀尀渀尀渀刀甀渀 琀栀攀 猀琀愀爀琀攀爀 挀漀搀攀Ⰰ 琀栀攀渀 挀漀洀瀀氀攀琀攀 琀栀攀 吀伀䐀伀猀⸀尀渀尀渀笀笀猀琀愀爀琀攀爀㨀尀渀搀攀昀 洀愀砀开猀甀戀愀爀爀愀礀开瀀爀漀搀甀挀琀开欀⠀愀爀爀Ⰰ 欀⤀㨀尀渀    椀昀 欀 㰀㴀 　 漀爀 欀 㸀 氀攀渀⠀愀爀爀⤀㨀尀渀        爀攀琀甀爀渀 　尀渀尀渀    挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 㴀 ㄀尀渀    昀漀爀 椀 椀渀 爀愀渀最攀⠀欀⤀㨀尀渀        挀甀爀爀攀渀琀 ⨀㴀 愀爀爀嬀椀崀尀渀尀渀    洀愀砀椀洀甀洀 㴀 挀甀爀爀攀渀琀尀渀尀渀    昀