+= 1\n\n        elif left[i] < right[j]:\n            if not result or result[-1] != left[i]:\n                result.append(left[i])\n            i += 1\n\n        else:\n            if not result or result[-1] != right[j]:\n                result.append(right[j])\n            j += 1\n\n    while i < len(left):\n        if not result or result[-1] != left[i]:\n            result.append(left[i])\n        i += 1\n\n    while j < len(right):\n        if not result or result[-1] != right[j]:\n            result.append(right[j])\n        j += 1\n\n    return result\n\nprint(merge_unique([1, 2, 2, 4], [2, 3, 4, 5]))\n}}\n\n{{answer: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=COk73cpQbFQ',2,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 20:15:24',NULL,'python'),('3ece8601-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3ecc364e-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Apply Dynamic Programming to Classic Problems','mixed',1,'Learn to solve classic dynamic programming problems using **memoization** and **tabulation** in Python. This lesson shows how to convert exponential recursive solutions into efficient DP implementations, why both techniques matter for time complexity, and a common pitfall where memo storage or table initialization is incorrect. You\'ll run and compare both approaches on Fibonacci numbers to validate correctness.','## What is dynamic programming **Dynamic programming (DP)** is a technique that transforms expensive recursive solutions into efficient algorithms by storing intermediate results. The two main DP strategies are **memoization** (top-down caching) and **tabulation** (bottom-up iterative building). Both use the same recurrence but differ in execution order. ## Why it matters DP reduces exponential time recurrences to polynomial or linear time in many classic problems (Fibonacci, knapsack, coin change). For intermediate developers, mastering DP enables solving interview-style problems and optimizing real-world workloads that exhibit overlapping subproblems and optimal substructure. ## How it works 1. Identify a recurrence (e.g., `fib(n) = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2)`). 2. Memoization: implement the recurrence recursively and cache results in a dictionary to avoid repeated work. 3. Tabulation: allocate a table (`dp`) and iteratively fill it from base cases upward until the desired index. 4. Verify both approaches return the same result for the same input and compare time complexity: memoization and tabulation both achieve O(n) time and O(n) space in the Fibonacci example. Example (short): ```python def fib_memo(n, memo={}): if n in memo: return memo[n] if n <= 1: return n memo[n] = fib_memo(n-1, memo) + fib_memo(n-2, memo) return memo[n] def fib_tab(n): if n <= 1: return n dp = [0] * (n + 1) dp[1] = 1 for i in range(2, n + 1): dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2] return dp[n] print(fib_memo(10), fib_tab(10)) ``` ## Common mistakes - Forgetting to initialize the memo/table properly leading to KeyError or incorrect base values; fix by explicitly setting base cases and using `memo=None` or resetting mutable defaults. - Using memoization with a shared mutable default (e.g., `memo={}` in function signature) across calls; fix by creating a new dictionary inside the function when `None` is passed. - Mixing up indices in tabulation (`dp[0]` vs `dp[1]`) which shifts results; fix by carefully defining base cases before the loop. ## Summary - DP uses **memoization** (top-down caching) and **tabulation** (bottom-up table). - Identify recurrence and base cases first, then store intermediate results. - Both approaches convert exponential recursion into linear time for Fibonacci. - Verify correctness by comparing both methods on sample inputs.\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oBt53YbR9Kk}}\n\nExample:\n\n```def fib_memo(n, memo={}):\n    if n in memo:\n        return memo[n]\n    if n <= 1:\n        return n\n    memo[n] = fib_memo(n-1, memo) + fib_memo(n-2, memo)\n    return memo[n]\n\ndef fib_tab(n):\n    if n <= 1:\n        return n\n    dp = [0] * (n + 1)\n    dp[1] = 1\n    for i in range(2, n + 1):\n        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2]\n    return dp[n]\n\nprint(fib_memo(10), fib_tab(10))\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n# Memoization (Top-down)\ndef ways_memo(n, memo={}):\n    if n in memo:\n        return memo[n]\n    if n <= 1:\n        return 1\n\n    memo[n] = ways_memo(n-1, memo) + ways_memo(n-2, memo)\n    return memo[n]\n\n\n# Tabulation (Bottom-up)\ndef ways_tab(n):\n    if n <= 1:\n        return 1\n\n    dp = [0] * (n + 1)\n    dp[0] = dp[1] = 1\n\n    for i in range(2, n + 1):\n        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2]\n\n    return dp[n]\n\n\nprint(ways_memo(5), ways_tab(5))\n}}\n\n{{answer: 8 8}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oBt53YbR9Kk',3,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 20:16:37',NULL,'python'),('3ecf1015-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3ecc364e-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Handle Performance Constraints and Worst-case Inputs','mixed',1,'Learn how to adapt algorithms for strict time and memory limits and how to design tests that expose worst-case behavior. This lesson shows why worst-case inputs matter, how to craft tests that reveal pathological performance, and one common pitfall: relying on average-case guarantees without safeguards against adversarial inputs.','# # What is worst-case input and performance constraints **Worst-case input ** refers to data that forces an algorithm to take the maximum resources (time or memory) it can require. ** Performance constraints ** are limits you must meet (e.g., time per request, memory footprint). This lesson focuses on recognizing, testing for, and mitigating worst-case scenarios so algorithms remain reliable under strict limits. # # Why it matters Real systems face adversarial or degenerate inputs: user-supplied data, long-running streams, or automated testers. An algorithm that performs well on average but degrades badly in the worst case can cause timeouts, outages, or excessive memory use. Designing for worst-case keeps systems robust and predictable. # # How it works 1. Identify the algorithmic complexity and memory bounds of your approach (e.g., O(n^2) time or O(n) memory). 2. Construct tests that force the worst-case behavior for that algorithm. For a naive pair-sum search, a list with no valid pairs forces all comparisons. 3. Replace or mitigate expensive steps: use hashing to trade time for memory (O(n) time, O(n) memory) or change pivot selection in quicksort to avoid O(n^2) on sorted inputs. 4. Measure with realistic limits and include early exits or resource guards when necessary. # # Common mistakes - Assuming average-case is sufficient: some libraries or patterns have adversarial worst cases; ** add safeguards ** like randomized choices or different data structures. - Not designing tests for pathological inputs: a missing test for \\\"no match\\\" or sorted input can hide O(n^2) behavior; ** create targeted worst-case inputs **. - Ignoring memory trade-offs: switching to a hash-based approach speeds up time but uses more memory; ** balance with constraints ** and consider streaming or chunking. # # Summary - ** Detect ** potential worst-case inputs early. - ** Design tests ** that force maximal work for the algorithm. - ** Mitigate ** with alternative data structures or randomized choices. - ** Measure** and balance time vs memory trade-offs. ```python # produce a list that has no two numbers summing to the target # this forces a full search when using a naive pair check def generate_no_pair(n, start=1): nums = list(range(start, start + n)) return nums print(generate_no_pair(5, start=1)) ```\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://wiki.python.org/moin/TimeComplexity\n\n- https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#set\n\n- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V6mKVRU1evU}}\n\nExample:\n\n```def has_pair_sum(nums, target):\n    seen = set()\n    for x in nums:\n        if target - x in seen:\n            return True\n        seen.add(x)\n    return False\n\nprint(has_pair_sum([2, 4, 5, 7, 11], 9))\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n# naive pair-sum search using nested loops\nnums = [2, 4, 5, 7, 11]\ntarget = 9\n\ndef find_pair_bruteforce(nums, target):\n    # iterate over all distinct pairs\n    for i in range(len(nums)):\n        for j in range(i + 1, len(nums)):\n            if nums[i] + nums[j] == target:\n                return nums[i], nums[j]\n\n    return None\n\n\npair = find_pair_bruteforce(nums, target)\n\nif pair is not None:\n    print(f\"Found pair: {pair[0]} and {pair[1]}\")\nelse:\n    print(\"No pair found\")\n}}\n\n{{answer: Found pair: 2 and 7}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V6mKVRU1evU',4,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 20:20:45',NULL,'python'),('3ecfa011-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','3ecc364e-5522-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Optimize and Prepare Solutions for Interviews and Production','mixed',1,'Learn how to polish algorithm solutions: verify correctness, add deterministic micro-profiling, and format answers for interviews or production. This lesson shows why small deterministic metrics beat noisy time measurements for reproducible tuning, how to add lightweight checks and operation counters, and common pitfalls like using non-deterministic timing in tests or leaking internal debug output into final submissions.','## What is polishing and preparing algorithmic solutions Polishing and preparing solutions means finalizing an algorithm so it\'s correct, efficient, and presentable for interviews or production. It includes adding deterministic, reproducible checks, lightweight profiling (operation counters or small inputs), clear input/output formatting, and small defensive validations. The goal is reliability and clarity, not deep benchmarking. ## Why it matters Interviewers expect concise, correct, and explainable solutions; production requires predictable performance and minimal debug noise. Using **deterministic profiling** and formatting ensures you can reproduce behavior, defend complexity claims, and avoid flaky timing results. A common pitfall is relying on wall-clock timing for micro-optimizations, which yields noisy, environment-dependent feedback. ## How it works 1. Add small, deterministic metrics such as an **operation counter** or iteration counts rather than raw time. This gives repeatable signals about algorithmic cost. 2. Add lightweight input validation and clear return types, e.g. return indices or a clear error indicator; avoid printing internal state in production outputs. 3. Use simple unit-style checks and example runs to verify correctness before formatting for an interview platform; keep debug output separate from the final return. 4. When profiling, prefer `timeit` or counters for repeatable microbenchmarks and reserve `cProfile` for broader runtime analysis. ## Common mistakes - Printing debugging details directly instead of returning clean results; fix by separating `return` vs `print` and turning debug prints behind a flag. - Using wall-clock time as the primary measure for micro-optimizations; fix by using deterministic counters or averaged `timeit` runs. - Forgetting edge-case handling (empty inputs, no solution); fix by adding short validation and documented failure behavior. ## Summary - Use **deterministic counters** to measure algorithmic steps for reproducible tuning. - Keep production output clean: `return` values, not debug prints. - Validate edge cases and document failure behavior. - Use small example runs combined with counters to defend complexity claims in interviews. ```python # Example: two-sum with an operation counter for deterministic profiling def two_sum(nums, target): ops = 0 seen = {} for i, n in enumerate(nums): ops += 1 comp = target - n if comp in seen: return [seen[comp], i], ops seen[n] = i return [], ops nums = [2, 7, 11, 15] result, ops = two_sum(nums, 9) print(result) print(f\"operations: {ops}\") ```\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://docs.python.org/3/library/timeit.html\n\n- https://docs.python.org/3/library/profile.html\n\n\nExample:\n\n```def two_sum(nums, target):\n    ops = 0\n    seen = {}\n    for i, n in enumerate(nums):\n        ops += 1\n        comp = target - n\n        if comp in seen:\n            return [seen[comp], i], ops\n        seen[n] = i\n    return [], ops\n\nprint(two_sum([2, 7, 11, 15], 9))\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\ndef two_sum(nums, target):\n    ops = 0\n    seen = {}\n\n    for i, n in enumerate(nums):\n        ops += 1\n        comp = target - n\n\n        if comp in seen:\n            return [seen[comp], i], ops\n\n        seen[n] = i\n\n    return [], ops\n\n\n# Starter scenario\nnums = [2, 7, 11, 15]\nresult, ops = two_sum(nums, 9)\n\nprint(result)\nprint(f\"operations: {ops}\")\n}}\n\n{{answer: [0, 1] operations: 2}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8mAITcNt710',5,15,1,'2026-05-21 17:34:59','2026-05-21 20:21:44',NULL,'python'),('724d00e3-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','724c6c24-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Install JDK and configure PATH on your OS','text',0,'Install the Java Development Kit (JDK) and set the JAVA_HOME and PATH environment variables for Windows, macOS, and Linux. Why: compiling and running java programs from the command line requires the javac and java executables to be discoverable. What to watch for: multiple Java versions, permission issues, and incorrect JAVA_HOME vs PATH entries that prevent tools and IDEs from locating the right runtime. Includes verification steps and common fixes.','Lesson: Install JDK and configure PATH on your OS\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://openjdk.java.net/install/\n\n- https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/install/index.html\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8cm1x4bC610}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8cm1x4bC610',1,10,0,'2026-05-15 19:38:04','2026-05-15 19:38:04',NULL,'javascript'),('724e6ae5-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','724c6c24-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Create and Run a Java Project in an IDE','mixed',1,'Create, configure, and run a basic Java project inside IntelliJ or Eclipse, covering project structure, JDK/SDK setup, source folders, main class, and the build/run lifecycle. This lesson explains why IDE configuration and correct SDK selection matter for compiling and running code, and highlights a common pitfall: missing or misconfigured project SDK/main method, which causes runtime or compilation failures and confusing IDE errors.','Lesson: Create and Run a Java Project in an IDE\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/console/log\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide\n\n- https://nodejs.org/en/docs/guides/getting-started-guide/\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PkZNo7MFNFg}}\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Simulate key checks when creating and running a Java project in an IDE\n function setupProject() { // simulate SDK configured correctly in the IDE\n const sdkConfigured = true; // simulate presence of a main method / entry point\n const hasMain = true;\n if (sdkConfigured && hasMain) { // final runtime message shown when project runs successfully \nconsole.log(\'java project run successful\'); \n} else { \nconsole.log(\'java project run failed\');\n } } \nsetupProject();\n}}\n\n{{answer: java project run successful}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PkZNo7MFNFg',2,15,0,'2026-05-15 19:38:04','2026-05-15 19:41:10',NULL,'javascript'),('724f9b69-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','724c6c24-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Compile and run Java programs using javac and java','code_example',1,'Show how to compile .java sources into .class files with javac and launch Java applications with the java command from the terminal. Youظـزظــظ꓂㐀Ⰶ숥ظـز╪زll learn exact command forms, common flags, and how to structure source filenames to match public classes. This prevents runtime errors and ClassNotFound exceptions. Pitfall: mismatched file/class names or wrong classpath and PATH configuration can cause compilation or launcher failures.','Lesson: Compile and run Java programs using javac and java\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://nodejs.org/api/child_process.html\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=grEKMHGYyns}}\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Simulate compiling and running a Java program // In real life you run: javac HelloWorld.java // then: java HelloWorld const source = \'HelloWorld.java\'; const classFile = \'helloworld class\'; // final console output demonstrates successful compile and run console.log(\'compiled \' + classFile + \' and ran helloworld main\');\n}}\n\n{{answer: compiled helloworld class and ran helloworld main}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=grEKMHGYyns',3,15,0,'2026-05-15 19:38:04','2026-05-15 19:38:04',NULL,'javascript'),('7250f247-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','724c6c24-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Write a main method and structure a Java class','code_example',1,'Show how to write a public static void main method and organize a Java class with package and import declarations placed correctly. Why: main is the JVM entry point and correct placement prevents compilation and runtime errors. Covers class declaration, where to put package and import statements, and common pitfalls such as placing package after imports, misnaming the file, or using an incorrect main signature.','Lesson: Write a main method and structure a Java class\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://nodejs.org/en/docs/\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Java example (for learning only): /* package com.example; import java.util.*; public class HelloWorld { public static void main(String[] args) { System.out.println(\"Hello from main\"); } } */ // Simulate running the Java program output in this live editor: console.log(\"hello from main\");\n}}\n\n{{answer: hello from main}}',NULL,4,15,0,'2026-05-15 19:38:04','2026-05-15 19:38:04',NULL,'javascript'),('7251a549-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','724c6c24-507c-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Declare and use primitive types, variables, and literals','code_example',1,'Declare common Java primitive variables (int, boolean, double, char), assign literals, and perform simple operations. Learn why selecting the right primitive matters for memory and correctness, and how literals map to types. Watch for a common pitfall: mixing types without casting or assuming floating-point precision, which leads to subtle bugs in arithmetic and comparisons.','Lesson: Declare and use primitive types, variables, and literals\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide/Grammar_and_types\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/let\n\n- https://nodejs.org/api/console.html\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\n// Demonstration of Java-like primitives using JavaScript variables const intVal = 5; // int const boolVal = true; // boolean const doubleVal = \'3point14\'; // represent double 3.14 as text to avoid punctuation in output const charVal = \'a\'; // char (lowercase) // Summary output (single line, all lowercase, no punctuation) console.log(\'int \' + intVal + \' boolean \' + boolVal + \' double \' + doubleVal + \' char \' + charVal);\n}}\n\n{{answe