t semantic grouping communicates to browsers, assistive tech, and search engines; why div/span remain necessary for styling, scripting, or when no semantic element fits; and the pitfall of overusing non-semantic containers that reduce accessibility and document clarity. You\'ll get concrete examples and quick rules-of-thumb for choosing appropriately.','Lesson: Apply semantic grouping with div and span when needed\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Semantics\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/div\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/span\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Rs2ND1ryYc}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n  <body>\n    <article>\n      <h2>Article Title</h2>\n      <p>Semantic content that screen readers can navigate.</p>\n    </article>\n\n<div class=\"card\">\n      <h3>Card title</h3>\n      <p><span class=\"muted\">Meta:</span> This uses div and span for layout and small inline text.</p>\n    </div>\n  </body>\n</html>\n```','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Rs2ND1ryYc',2,10,0,'2026-05-15 19:47:33','2026-05-15 19:47:33',NULL,'javascript'),('c5246be6-507d-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','c523bee3-507d-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Create accessible forms with labels, inputs, and fieldset','code_example',1,'Build accessible HTML forms by associating labels with inputs and grouping related controls using fieldset and legend. This lesson shows two association patternsظـزظــظ꓂㐀Ⰶ숥ظ꓂㐀樆㐥氆愀戀攀氀 眀椀琀栀 昀漀爀⼀椀搀 愀渀搀 氀愀戀攀氀 眀爀愀瀀瀀椀渀最㠀䀆㈆㠆䀆䀆㠆숆¤ش┬胂㠀숆¤ش╪شexplains why screen readers and keyboard users depend on them, and demonstrates grouping with fieldset/legend. Follow best practices for required fields and focus states. Pitfall: unlabeled inputs or incorrect for attributes break accessibility and confuse assistive technologies.','Lesson: Create accessible forms with labels, inputs, and fieldset\n\n> Note: Live JavaScript editor runs in the browser. Avoid `require`, `process`, and server startup code here.\n\nUseful Resources:\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/label\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/fieldset\n\n- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/legend\n\n{{video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7l3V7Q8q0Ic}}\n\nExample:\n\n```code\n<form>\n  <fieldset>\n    <legend>Contact</legend>\n    <label for=\"email\">Email</label>\n    <input id=\"email\" name=\"email\" type=\"email\">\n    <label>Phone <input name=\"phone\" type=\"tel\"></label>\n  </fieldset>\n</form>\n```\n\nLive Coding Task:\n\nRun the starter code, then complete the TODOs.\n\n{{starter:\nconst formHTML = ` <form id=\"signup\"> <fieldset> <legend>Account</legend> <!-- label associated via for/id --> <label for=\"username\">Username</label> <input id=\"username\" name=\"username\" /> <!-- label wrapping the input --> <label>Password <input id=\"password\" name=\"password\" /></label> <!-- unlabeled input to illustrate a pitfall --> <input id=\"noLabel\" name=\"noLabel\" /> </fieldset> </form> `; // Render the form into the document (browser-safe) document.body.innerHTML = formHTML; // Count labels that are properly associated with a control const labels = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll(\'label\')); const associated = labels.filter(label => { const forId = label.getAttribute(\'for\'); if (forId) return !!document.getElementById(forId); return !!label.querySelector(\'input,select,textarea\'); }); const count = associated.length; const output = count === 2 ? \'two labels associated\' : (count === 1 ? \'one label associated\' : `${count} labels associated`); console.log(output);\n}}\n\n{{answer: two labels associated}}','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7l3V7Q8q0Ic',3,15,0,'2026-05-15 19:47:33','2026-05-15 19:47:33',NULL,'javascript'),('c5254d75-507d-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','c523bee3-507d-11f1-9abe-6c02e0d26821','Implement tables for tabular data with thead, tbody, tr, t